enge Stadium]]\n|report=[http://match.nadeshikoleague.jp/2015/cl_exm/match_report/m3.pdf]\n}}\n\n* ''Tsukuba F.C. Ladies'' Stay Division 3 (Challenge League) in 2016 Season.\n* ''INAC Kobe Leoncheena'' Stay Regional League (Kansai League) in 2016 Season.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==See also==\n*[[Empress's Cup]]\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|ja}} [http://www.nadeshikoleague.jp/ Nadeshiko League Official Site]\n* [http://int.women.soccerway.com/national/japan/l1-league/2014/championship-round/r29267/ Season] at soccerway.com\n\n{{L. League seasons}}\n\n[[Category:Nadeshiko League seasons]]\n[[Category:2014 in Japanese women's football|1]]\n[[Category:2014 in Japanese football leagues|L]]\n[[Category:2014\u201315 domestic women's association football leagues|Japan]]\n[[Category:2013\u201314 domestic women's association football leagues|Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Frietjes", "label": "safe", "comment": "expand templates perFb team TfD outcomeandFb competition TfD outcomeandFb cl TfD outcomeandFb rbr TfD outcome", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_Nadeshiko_League"}
{"title_page": "Ototoxicity", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Ototoxicity \n| image           =  \n| caption         =  \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           = [[Otorhinolaryngology]]\n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Ototoxicity''' is the <!-- changed from 'quality' to property (hardly a quality) -->property of being [[toxicity|toxic]] to the [[ear]] (''oto-''), specifically the [[cochlea]] or [[vestibulocochlear nerve|auditory nerve]] and sometimes the [[vestibular system]], for example, as a side effect of a drug. The effects of ototoxicity can be reversible and temporary, or irreversible and permanent. \nIt has been recognized since the 19th century.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schacht J, Hawkins JE | title = Sketches of otohistory. Part 11: Ototoxicity: drug-induced hearing loss | journal = Audiology and Neuro-Otology | volume = 11 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u20136 | date = 2006-01-01 | pmid = 16219991 | doi = 10.1159/000088850 }}</ref> \nThere are many well-known ototoxic drugs used in clinical situations, and they are prescribed, despite the risk of hearing disorders, to very serious health conditions.<ref>{{cite book | url = http://audiology-web.s3.amazonaws.com/migrated/OtoMonGuidelines.pdf_539974c40999c1.58842217.pdf | title = Position Statement and Practice Guidelines on Ototoxicity Monitoring | publisher = American Academy of Audiology | year = 2009 }}</ref> \nOtotoxic drugs include [[antibiotic]]s such as [[gentamicin]], [[streptomycin]], [[tobramycin]], [[loop diuretic]]s such as [[furosemide]] and [[platinum]]-based [[chemotherapy]] agents such as [[cisplatin]], [[carboplatin]], and [[vincristine]]. A number of [[nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug]]s (NSAIDS) have also been shown to be ototoxic.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cazals Y | title = Auditory sensori-neural alterations induced by salicylate | journal = Progress in Neurobiology | volume = 62 | issue = 6 | pages = 583\u2013631 | date = December 2000 | pmid = 10880852 | doi = 10.1016/s0301-0082(00)00027-7 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jung|first=T. T.|last2=Rhee|first2=C. K.|last3=Lee|first3=C. S.|last4=Park|first4=Y. S.|last5=Choi|first5=D. C.|date=October 1993|title=Ototoxicity of salicylate, nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drugs, and quinine|journal=Otolaryngologic Clinics of North America|volume=26|issue=5|pages=791\u2013810|issn=0030-6665|pmid=8233489}}</ref> This can result in [[sensorineural hearing loss]], [[dysequilibrium]], or both. Some environmental and occupational chemicals have also been shown to affect the [[auditory system]] and interact with noise.<ref name=\"Johnson_2010\">{{cite journal| vauthors = Johnson AC, Morata TC | date = 2010 | title = Occupational exposure to chemicals and hearing impairment. The Nordic Expert Group for Criteria Documentation of Health Risks from Chemicals | url = https://gupea.ub.gu.se/bitstream/2077/23240/1/gupea_2077_23240_1.pdf | journal = Arbete och H\u00e4lsa |volume=44 |issue=4 |pages=177|doi=|pmid=|access-date=May 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nSymptoms of ototoxicity include partial or profound [[Hearing impairment|hearing loss]], [[Vertigo (medical)|vertigo]], and [[tinnitus]].<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\nThe cochlea is primarily a hearing structure situated in the inner ear. It is the snail-shaped shell containing several nerve endings that makes hearing possible.<ref name=Farlex>{{cite web|url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/ototoxicity|work=The Free Dictionary by Farlex|title=ototoxicity}}</ref>\nOtotoxicity typically results when the inner ear is poisoned by medication that damages the cochlea, vestibule, semi-circular canals, or the auditory/ vestibulocochlear nerve. The damaged structure then produces the symptoms the patient presents with. Ototoxicity in the cochlea may cause hearing loss of the high-frequency pitch ranges or complete deafness, or losses at points between.<ref name=Mudd>{{cite web|last=Mudd|first=Pamela | name-list-format = vanc |title=Ototoxicity|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/857679-overview|work=Medscape Reference|publisher=WebMD LLC|accessdate=30 Nov 2011}}</ref>  It may present with bilaterally symmetrical symptoms, or asymmetrically, with one ear developing the condition after the other or not at all.<ref name=Mudd/> The time frames for progress of the disease vary greatly and symptoms of hearing loss may be temporary or permanent.<ref name=Farlex/>\n\nThe [[vestibule of the ear|vestibule]] and [[semi-circular canal]] are inner-ear components that comprise the vestibular system. Together they detect all directions of head movement. Two types of [[otolith organs]] are housed in the vestibule: the [[saccule]], which points vertically and detects vertical acceleration, and the [[utricle (ear)|utricle]], which points horizontally and detects horizontal acceleration. The otolith organs together sense the head's position with respect to gravity when the body is static; then the head's movement when it tilts; and pitch changes during any linear motion of the head. The saccule and utricle detect different motions, which information the brain receives and integrates to determine where the head is and how and where it is moving.\n\nThe semi-circular canals are three bony structures filled with fluid. As with the vestibule, the primary purpose of the canals is to detect movement. Each canal is oriented at right angles to the others, enabling detection of movement in any plane. The posterior canal detects rolling motion, or motion about the X axis; the anterior canal detects pitch, or motion about the Y axis; the horizontal canal detects yaw motion, or motion about the Z axis. \nWhen a medication is toxic in the vestibule or the semi-circular canals, the patient senses loss of balance or orientation rather than losses in hearing. Symptoms in these organs present as vertigo, difficulties walking in low light and darkness, disequilibrium, oscillopsia among others.<ref name=Mudd/> Each of these problems is related to balance and the mind is confused with the direction of motion or lack of motion. Both the vestibule and semi-circular canals transmit information to the brain about movement; when these are poisoned, they are unable to function properly which results in miscommunication with the brain.\n\nWhen the vestibule and/or semi-circular canals are affected by ototoxicity, the eye can also be affected. [[Nystagmus]] and [[oscillopsia]] are two conditions that overlap the vestibular and ocular systems. These symptoms cause the patient to have difficulties with seeing and processing images. The body subconsciously tries to compensate for the imbalance signals being sent to the brain by trying to obtain visual cues to support the information it is receiving. This results in that dizziness and \"woozy\" feeling patients use to describe conditions such as oscillopsia and vertigo.<ref name=Mudd/>\n\n[[Cranial nerve VIII]] is the least affected component of the ear when ototoxicity arises, but if the nerve is affected, the damage is most often permanent. Symptoms present similar to those resulting from vestibular and cochlear damage, including tinnitus, ringing of the ears, difficulty walking, deafness, and balance and orientation issues.\n\n==Ototoxic agents==\n\n===Antibiotics===\nAntibiotics in the [[aminoglycoside]] class, such as [[gentamicin]] and [[tobramycin]], may produce cochleotoxicity through a poorly understood mechanism.<ref name=\"pmid16549744\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dobie RA, Black FO, Pezsnecker SC, Stallings VL | title = Hearing loss in patients with vestibulotoxic reactions to gentamicin therapy | journal = Archives of Otolaryngology\u2013Head & Neck Surgery | volume = 132 | issue = 3 | pages = 253\u20137 | date = March 2006 | pmid = 16549744 | doi = 10.1001/archotol.132.3.253 | doi-access = free }}</ref> It may result from antibiotic binding to [[NMDA receptor]]s in the [[cochlea]] and damaging [[neuron]]s through [[excitotoxicity]].<ref name=\"pmid8946832\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Basile AS, Huang JM, Xie C, Webster D, Berlin C, Skolnick P | title = N-methyl-D-aspartate antagonists limit aminoglycoside antibiotic-induced hearing loss | journal = Nature Medicine | volume = 2 | issue = 12 | pages = 1338\u201343 | date = December 1996 | pmid = 8946832 | doi = 10.1038/nm1296-1338 }}</ref> Aminoglycoside-induced production of [[reactive oxygen species]] may also injure cells of the [[cochlea]].<ref name=\"pmid12053140\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wu WJ, Sha SH, Schacht J | title = Recent advances in understanding aminoglycoside ototoxicity and its prevention | journal = Audiology and Neuro-Otology | volume = 7 | issue = 3 | pages = 171\u20134 | year = 2002 | pmid = 12053140 | doi = 10.1159/000058305 }}</ref> Once-daily dosing<ref name=\"pmid8722531\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Munckhof WJ, Grayson ML, Turnidge JD | title = A meta-analysis of studies on the safety and efficacy of aminoglycosides given either once daily or as divided doses | journal = The Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy | volume = 37 | issue = 4 | pages = 645\u201363 | date = April 1996 | pmid = 8722531 | doi = 10.1093/jac/37.4.645 | doi-access = free }}</ref> and co-administration of [[N-acetylcysteine|''N''-acetylcysteine]]<ref name=\"pmid17653228\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tepel M | title = N-Acetylcysteine in the prevention of ototoxicity | journal = Kidney International | volume = 72 | issue = 3 | pages = 231\u20132 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17653228 | doi = 10.1038/sj.ki.5002299 }}</ref> may protect against aminoglycoside-induced ototoxicity. The anti-bacterial activity of aminoglycoside compounds is due to inhibition of ribosome function and these compounds similarly inhibit protein synthesis by mitochondrial ribosomes because mitochondria evolved from a bacterial ancestor.<ref name=\"pmid17116475\">{{Cite book | vauthors = Wirmer J, Westhof E | title = Molecular contacts between antibiotics and the 30S ribosomal particle | journal = Methods in Enzymology | volume = 415 | pages = 180\u2013202 | date = 2006 | pmid = 17116475 | doi = 10.1016/S0076-6879(06)15012-0 | isbn = 9780121828202 }}</ref> Consequently, aminoglycoside effects on production of reactive oxygen species as well as dysregulation of cellular calcium ion homeostasis may result from disruption of mitochondrial function.<ref name=\"pmid23616556\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Esterberg R, Hailey DW, Coffin AB, Raible DW, Rubel EW | title = Disruption of intracellular calcium regulation is integral to aminoglycoside-induced hair cell death | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 33 | issue = 17 | pages = 7513\u201325 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23616556 | pmc = 3703319 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4559-12.2013 }}</ref> Ototoxicity of gentamicin can be exploited to treat some individuals with [[M\u00e9ni\u00e8re's disease]] by destroying the inner ear,  which stops the vertigo attacks but causes permanent deafness.<ref name=\"pmid12616197\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Perez N, Mart\u00edn E, Garc\u00eda-Tapia R | title = Intratympanic gentamicin for intractable Meniere's disease | journal = The Laryngoscope | volume = 113 | issue = 3 | pages = 456\u201364 | date = March 2003 | pmid = 12616197 | doi = 10.1097/00005537-200303000-00013 }}</ref>\nDue to the effects on mitochondria, certain inherited mitochondrial disorders result in increased sensitivity to the toxic effects of aminoglycosides.\n\n[[Macrolide]] antibiotics, including [[erythromycin]], are associated with reversible ototoxic effects.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> The underlying mechanism of ototoxicity may be impairment of [[ion transport]] in the [[stria vascularis]].<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> Predisposing factors include [[renal impairment]], [[hepatic impairment]], and recent [[organ transplantation]].<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\n===Loop diuretics===\nCertain types of diuretics are associated with varying levels of risk for ototoxicity. Loop and thiazide diuretics carry this side effect. The [[loop diuretic]] [[furosemide]] is associated with ototoxicity, particularly when doses exceed 240&nbsp;mg per hour.<ref name=\"pmid3430953\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Voelker JR, Cartwright-Brown D, Anderson S, Leinfelder J, Sica DA, Kokko JP, Brater DC | title = Comparison of loop diuretics in patients with chronic renal insufficiency | journal = Kidney International | volume = 32 | issue = 4 | pages = 572\u20138 | date = October 1987 | pmid = 3430953 | doi = 10.1038/ki.1987.246 }}</ref> The related compound [[ethacrynic acid]] has a higher association with ototoxicity, and is therefore used only in patients with sulfa allergies. Diuretics are thought to alter the ionic gradient within the [[Stria vascularis of cochlear duct|stria vascularis]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Schmitz | first1 = Paul G. | name-list-format = vanc | title = Renal: An Integrated Approach to Disease | date = 2012 | publisher = McGraw-Hill | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-07-162155-7 | page = 123 }}</ref> [[Bumetanide]] confers a decreased risk of ototoxicity compared to furosemide.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\">{{cite book | last = Roland | first = Peter S. | name-list-format = vanc | title = Ototoxicity | publisher = B.C. Decker | location = Hamilton, Ont | year = 2004 |pages= |isbn=978-1-55009-263-9 }}</ref>\n\n===Chemotherapeutic agents===\n[[Platinum]]-containing chemotherapeutic agents, including [[cisplatin]] and [[carboplatin]], are associated with cochleotoxicity characterized by progressive, high-frequency hearing loss with or without [[tinnitus]] (ringing in the ears).<ref name=\"pmid16484702\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rademaker-Lakhai JM, Crul M, Zuur L, Baas P, Beijnen JH, Simis YJ, van Zandwijk N, Schellens JH | title = Relationship between cisplatin administration and the development of ototoxicity | journal = Journal of Clinical Oncology | volume = 24 | issue = 6 | pages = 918\u201324 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16484702 | doi = 10.1200/JCO.2006.10.077 }}</ref> Ototoxicity is less frequently seen with the related compound [[oxaliplatin]].<ref name=\"pmid19116379\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hellberg V, Wallin I, Eriksson S, Hernlund E, Jerremalm E, Berndtsson M, Eksborg S, Arn\u00e9r ES, Shoshan M, Ehrsson H, Laurell G | title = Cisplatin and oxaliplatin toxicity: importance of cochlear kinetics as a determinant for ototoxicity | journal = Journal of the National Cancer Institute | volume = 101 | issue = 1 | pages = 37\u201347 | date = January 2009 | pmid = 19116379 | pmc = 2639295 | doi = 10.1093/jnci/djn418 }}</ref> The severity of cisplatin-induced ototoxicity is dependent upon the cumulative dose administered<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bokemeyer C, Berger CC, Hartmann JT, Kollmannsberger C, Schmoll HJ, Kuczyk MA, Kanz L | title = Analysis of risk factors for cisplatin-induced ototoxicity in patients with testicular cancer | journal = British Journal of Cancer | volume = 77 | issue = 8 | pages = 1355\u201362 | date = April 1998 | pmid = 9579846 | pmc = 2150148  | doi = 10.1038/bjc.1998.226 }}</ref> and the age of the patient, with young children being most susceptible.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Li Y, Womer RB, Silber JH | title = Predicting cisplatin ototoxicity in children: the influence of age and the cumulative dose | journal = European Journal of Cancer | volume = 40 | issue = 16 | pages = 2445\u201351 | date = November 2004 | pmid = 15519518 | doi = 10.1016/j.ejca.2003.08.009  }}</ref> The exact mechanism of cisplatin ototoxicity is not known. The drug is understood to damage multiple regions of the cochlea, causing the death of outer [[hair cell]]s, as well as damage to the [[spiral ganglion]] neurons and cells of the [[Stria vascularis of cochlear duct|stria vascularis]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Callejo A, Sed\u00f3-Cabez\u00f3n L, Juan ID, Llorens J | title = Cisplatin-Induced Ototoxicity: Effects, Mechanisms and Protection Strategies | journal = Toxics | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 268\u2013293 | date = July 2015 | pmid = 29051464 | pmc = 5606684 | doi = 10.3390/toxics3030268 }}</ref> Long-term retention of cisplatin in the cochlea may contribute to the drug's cochleotoxic potential.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Breglio AM, Rusheen AE, Shide ED, Fernandez KA, Spielbauer KK, McLachlin KM, Hall MD, Amable L, Cunningham LL | title = Cisplatin is retained in the cochlea indefinitely following chemotherapy | journal = Nature Communications | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 1654 | date = November 2017 | pmid = 29162831 | pmc = 5698400 | doi = 10.1038/s41467-017-01837-1 }}</ref> Once inside the cochlea, cisplatin has been proposed to cause cellular toxicity through a number of different mechanisms, including through the production of [[reactive oxygen species]].<ref name=\"pmid17113254\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rybak LP, Whitworth CA, Mukherjea D, Ramkumar V | title = Mechanisms of cisplatin-induced ototoxicity and prevention | journal = Hearing Research | volume = 226 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 157\u201367 | date = April 2007 | pmid = 17113254 | doi = 10.1016/j.heares.2006.09.015 }}</ref> The decreased incidence of oxaliplatin ototoxicity has been attributed to decreased uptake of the drug by cells of the cochlea.<ref name=\"pmid19116379\"/> Administration of [[amifostine]] has been used in attempts to prevent cisplatin-induced ototoxicity, but the [[American Society of Clinical Oncology]] recommends against its routine use.<ref name=\"pmid19018081\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hensley ML, Hagerty KL, Kewalramani T, Green DM, Meropol NJ, Wasserman TH, Cohen GI, Emami B, Gradishar WJ, Mitchell RB, Thigpen JT, Trotti A, von Hoff D, Schuchter LM | title = American Society of Clinical Oncology 2008 clinical practice guideline update: use of chemotherapy and radiation therapy protectants | journal = Journal of Clinical Oncology | volume = 27 | issue = 1 | pages = 127\u201345 | date = January 2009 | pmid = 19018081 | doi = 10.1200/JCO.2008.17.2627 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[vinca alkaloid|''vinca'' alkaloids]],<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = van Der Heijden R, Jacobs DI, Snoeijer W, Hallard D, Verpoorte R | title = The Catharanthus alkaloids: pharmacognosy and biotechnology | journal = Current Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 11 | issue = 5 | pages = 607\u201328 | date = March 2004 | pmid = 15032608 | doi = 10.2174/0929867043455846 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last = Ravi\u00f1a|first = Enrique | name-list-format = vanc |title = The evolution of drug discovery: From traditional medicines to modern drugs|year = 2011|publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons]] | isbn = 978-3-527-32669-3 | pages = 157\u2013159|chapter = Vinca alkaloids|chapter-url = https://books.google.ca/books?id=iDNy0XxGqT8C&pg=PA157}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter = Africa's gift to the world|pages = 46\u201351|chapter-url = https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aXGmCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46|title = Botanical Miracles: Chemistry of Plants That Changed the World|first1 = Raymond|last1 = Cooper|first2 = Jeffrey John|last2 = Deakin | name-list-format = vanc |publisher = [[CRC Press]]|year = 2016 | isbn = 978-1-4987-0430-4 }}</ref> including [[vincristine]],<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Keglevich P, Hazai L, Kalaus G, Sz\u00e1ntay C | title = Modifications on the basic skeletons of vinblastine and vincristine | journal = Molecules | volume = 17 | issue = 5 | pages = 5893\u2013914 | date = May 2012 | pmid = 22609781 | pmc = 6268133 | doi = 10.3390/molecules17055893 }}</ref> are also associated with reversible ototoxicity.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\n===Antiseptics and disinfectants===\n\nTopical skin preparations such as [[chlorhexidine]] and [[ethyl alcohol]] have the potential to be ototoxic should they enter the inner ear through the [[round window membrane]].<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> This potential was first noted after a small percentage of patients undergoing early [[myringoplasty]] operations experienced severe sensorineural hearing loss. It was found that in all operations involving this complication the preoperative sterilization was done with chlorhexidine.<ref>{{cite journal  |author=Bicknell, P. G. |title=Sensorineural deafness following myringoplasty operations |journal=The Journal of Laryngology & Otology |volume=85 |issue=9 |pages=957\u2013962 |date=1971 |doi=10.1017/S0022215100074272   }}</ref> The ototoxicity of chlorhexidine was further confirmed by studies with animal models.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\nSeveral other skin preparations have been shown to be potentially ototoxic in the animal model. These preparations include [[acetic acid]], [[propylene glycol]], [[quaternary ammonium compounds]], and any alcohol-based preparations. However, it is difficult to extrapolate these results to human ototoxicity because the human round window membrane is much thicker than in any animal model.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\n===Other medicinal ototoxic drugs===\nAt high doses, quinine, [[aspirin]] and other [[salicylate]]s may also cause high-pitch [[tinnitus]] and hearing loss in both ears, typically reversible upon discontinuation of the drug.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> Erectile dysfunction medications may have the potential to cause hearing loss.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/2007/ucm109012.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090709212332/https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/2007/ucm109012.htm | url-status = dead | archive-date = 9 July 2009 | title = FDA Announces Revisions to Labels for Cialis, Levitra and Viagra. Potential risk of sudden hearing loss with ED drugs to be displayed more prominently | publisher = United States Food and Drug Administration }}</ref> However the link between erectile dysfunction medications and hearing loss remains uncertain.<ref name=\"pmid28923561\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Yafi FA, Sharlip ID, Becher EF | title = Update on the Safety of Phosphodiesterase Type 5 Inhibitors for the Treatment of Erectile Dysfunction | journal = Sexual Medicine Reviews | volume = 6| issue = 2| pages = 242\u2013252| year = 2017 | pmid = 28923561 | doi = 10.1016/j.sxmr.2017.08.001 }}</ref>\n\nPrevious noise exposure has not been found to potentiate ototoxic hearing loss.<ref name=\"Campbell_2007\" /><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Laurell G, Borg E|date=1986-01-01|title=Cis-platin ototoxicity in previously noise-exposed guinea pigs|journal=Acta Oto-Laryngologica|volume=101|issue=1\u20132|pages=66\u201374|doi=10.3109/00016488609108609|pmid=3962651}}</ref> The American Academy of Audiology includes in their position statement that exposure to noise at the same time as [[aminoglycoside]]s may exacerbate ototoxicity. The American Academy of Audiology recommends people being treated with ototoxic chemotherapeutics avoid excessive noise levels during treatment and for several months following cessation of treatment. Opiates in combination with excessive noise levels may also have an additive effect on ototoxic hearing loss.<ref>{{cite book|title=Hearing Conservation in Occupational, Recreational, Educational, and Home Settings|last=Rawool|first=Vishakha Waman|publisher=Thieme|year=2012|isbn=978-1-60406-256-4|location=New York|pages=13|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref>\n\n=== Ototoxicants in the environment and workplace ===\nOtotoxic effects are also seen with [[quinine]], [[pesticide]]s, [[solvent]]s, [[Asphyxiant gas|asphyxiants]], and [[Heavy metal (chemistry)|heavy metal]]s such as [[mercury (element)|mercury]] and [[lead]].<ref name=\"Johnson_2010\" /><ref name=\"ototoxicity\" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Campo P, Morata TC, Hong O | title = Chemical exposure and hearing loss | journal = Disease-A-Month | volume = 59 | issue = 4 | pages = 119\u201338 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23507352 | pmc = 4693596 | doi = 10.1016/j.disamonth.2013.01.003 }}</ref> When combining multiple ototoxicants, the risk of hearing loss becomes greater.<ref>{{cite book | title = Hearing Conservation: In Occupational, Recreational, Educational, and Home settings | last = Rawool | first = Vishakha | name-list-format = vanc | publisher = Thieme | year = 2012 | location = New York, NY | pages = 10 | isbn = 978-1-60406-256-4 }}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Venet|first=Thomas|last2=Carreres-Pons|first2=Maria|last3=Chalansonnet|first3=Monique|last4=Thomas|first4=Aur\u00e9lie|last5=Merlen|first5=Lise|last6=Nunge|first6=Herv\u00e9|last7=Bonfanti|first7=Elodie|last8=Cosnier|first8=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last9=Llorens|first9=Jordi|date=2017-09-01|title=Continuous exposure to low-frequency noise and carbon disulfide: Combined effects on hearing|journal=NeuroToxicology|volume=62|pages=151\u2013161|doi=10.1016/j.neuro.2017.06.013|pmid=28655499|issn=0161-813X}}</ref> As these exposures are common, this hearing impairment can affect many occupations and industries.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Nordic Expert Group for criteria documentation of health risks from chemicals. 142, Occupational exposure to chemicals and hearing impairment|last=1955-|first=Johnson, Ann-Christin|date=2009|publisher=University of Gothenburg|others=Morata, Thais C.|isbn=9789185971213|location=G\u00f6teborg|oclc=939229378}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lewkowski|first=Kate|last2=Heyworth|first2=Jane S.|last3=Li|first3=Ian W.|last4=Williams|first4=Warwick|last5=McCausland|first5=Kahlia|last6=Gray|first6=Corie|last7=Ytterstad|first7=Elinor|last8=Glass|first8=Deborah C.|last9=Fuente|first9=Adrian|last10=Si|first10=Si|last11=Florath|first11=Ines|date=2019|title=Exposure to noise and ototoxic chemicals in the Australian workforce|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30683670|journal=Occupational and Environmental Medicine|volume=76|issue=5|pages=341\u2013348|doi=10.1136/oemed-2018-105471|issn=1470-7926|pmid=30683670|via=}}</ref>  Examples of activities that often have exposures to both noise and solvents include<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osha.gov/dts/shib/shib030818.html|title=Safety and Health Information Bulletins {{!}} Preventing Hearing Loss Caused by Chemical (Ototoxicity) and Noise Exposure {{!}} Occupational Safety and Health Administration|website=www.osha.gov|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>: \n\n* Printing\n* Painting\n* Construction\n* Fueling vehicles and aircraft\n* Firefighting\n* Weapons firing\n* Pesticide spraying\n\nOtotoxic chemicals in the environment (from contaminated air or water) or in the workplace interact with mechanical stresses on the hair cells of the cochlea in different ways. For mixtures containing organic solvents such as [[toluene]], [[styrene]] or [[xylene]], the combined exposure with noise increases the risk of occupational [[Occupational hearing loss|hearing loss]] in a [[synergy|synergistic]] manner.<ref name=\"Johnson_2010\" /><ref name=\"Fechter_2004\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fechter LD | title = Promotion of noise-induced hearing loss by chemical contaminants | journal = Journal of Toxicology and Environmental Health. Part A | volume = 67 | issue = 8\u201310 | pages = 727\u201340 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15192865 | doi = 10.1080/15287390490428206 }}</ref> The risk is greatest when the co-exposure is with impulse noise.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Venet|first=Thomas|last2=Campo|first2=Pierre|last3=Thomas|first3=Aur\u00e9lie|last4=Cour|first4=Chantal|last5=Rieger|first5=Beno\u00eet|last6=Cosnier|first6=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|title=The tonotopicity of styrene-induced hearing loss depends on the associated noise spectrum|journal=Neurotoxicology and Teratology|volume=48|pages=56\u201363|doi=10.1016/j.ntt.2015.02.003|pmid=25689156|year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fuente|first=Adrian|last2=Qiu|first2=Wei|last3=Zhang|first3=Meibian|last4=Xie|first4=Hongwei|last5=Kardous|first5=Chucri A.|last6=Campo|first6=Pierre|last7=Morata|first7=Thais C.|date=March 2018|title=Use of the kurtosis statistic in an evaluation of the effects of noise and solvent exposures on the hearing thresholds of workers: An exploratory study|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=143|issue=3|pages=1704|doi=10.1121/1.5028368|issn=1520-8524|pmid=29604694|url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01844639/file/10.1121_1.5028368.pdf}}</ref> [[Carbon monoxide]] has been shown to increase the severity of the hearing loss from noise.<ref name=\"Fechter_2004\" /> Given the potential for enhanced risk of hearing loss, exposures and contact with products such as fuels, paint thinners, degreasers, white spirits, exhaust, should be kept to a minimum.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2018-03-01|title=Preventing hearing loss caused by chemical (ototoxicity) and noise exposure.|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-124/|language=en|doi=10.26616/nioshpub2018124|doi-access=free}}</ref> Noise exposures should be kept below 85 decibels, and the chemical exposures should be below the recommended exposure limits given by regulatory agencies.\n\nDrug exposures mixed with noise potentially lead to increased risk of ototoxic hearing loss. Noise exposure combined with the chemotherapeutic [[cisplatin]] puts individuals at increased risk of ototoxic hearing loss.<ref name=\"Campbell_2007\">{{cite book | title = Pharmacology and Ototoxicity for Audiologists | last = Campbell | first = Kathleen | name-list-format = vanc | publisher = Delmar Centrage Learning | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-1-4180-1130-7 | location = Clifton Park, NY | pages = 145 }}</ref> Noise at 85&nbsp;dB SPL or above added to the amount of hair cell death in the high frequency region of the cochlea in chinchillas.<ref name=\"pmid2076973\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gratton MA, Salvi RJ, Kamen BA, Saunders SS | title = Interaction of cisplatin and noise on the peripheral auditory system | journal = Hearing Research | volume = 50 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 211\u201323 | year = 1990 | pmid = 2076973 | doi = 10.1016/0378-5955(90)90046-R }}</ref>\n\nThe hearing loss caused by chemicals can be very similar to a hearing loss caused by excessive noise.  A 2018 informational bulletin by the US [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration]] (OSHA) and the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] (NIOSH) introduces the issue, provides examples of ototoxic chemicals, lists the industries and occupations at risk and provides prevention information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-124/pdfs/2018-124.pdf|title=Preventing Hearing Loss Caused by Chemical (Ototoxicity) and Noise Exposure|last=Occupational Safety and Health Administration|first=National Institute for Occupational Safety and Heath|date=April 3, 2018|website=OSHA, NIOSH|archive-url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-124/pdfs/2018-124.pdf|archive-date=March 2018|url-status=|access-date=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Treatment==\nNo specific treatment may be available, but withdrawal of the ototoxic drug may be warranted when the consequences of doing so are less severe than those of the ototoxicity.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> Co-administration of anti-oxidants may limit the ototoxic effects.<ref name=\"Campbell_2007\" />\n\nOtotoxic monitoring during exposure is recommended by the American Academy of Audiology to allow for proper detection and possible prevention or rehabilitation of the hearing loss through a [[cochlear implant]] or [[hearing aid]]. Monitoring can be completed through performing [[otoacoustic emission]]s testing or high frequency [[audiometry]]. Successful monitoring includes a baseline test before, or soon after, exposure to the ototoxicant. Follow-up testing is completed in increments after the first exposure, throughout the cessation of treatment. Shifts in hearing status are monitored and relayed to the prescribing physician to make treatment decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://audiology-web.s3.amazonaws.com/migrated/OtoMonGuidelines.pdf_539974c40999c1.58842217.pdf|title=American Academy of Audiology Position Statement and Clinical Practice Guidelines: Ototoxic Monitoring | last = Durrant | first = John | name-list-format = vanc |date=October 2009 |website=American Academy of Audiology|publisher=American Academy of Audiology |access-date = 4 December 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIt is difficult to distinguish between nerve damage and structural damage due to similarity of the symptoms.  Diagnosis of ototoxicity typically results from ruling out all other possible sources of hearing loss and is often the catchall explanation for the symptoms. Treatment options vary depending on the patient and the diagnosis. Some patients experience only temporary symptoms that do not require drastic treatment while others can be treated with medication. Physical therapy may prove useful for regaining balance and walking abilities. [[Cochlear implant]]s are sometimes an option to restore hearing. Such treatments are typically taken to comfort the patient, not to cure the disease or damage caused by ototoxicity. There is no cure or restoration capability if the damage becomes permanent,<ref>{{cite web|last=My Deafness|title=Ototoxicity: Ear Poisoning|url=http://www.mydeafness.com/ototoxicity-ear-poisoning|work=Causes of Deafness and Types of Deafness (Hearing Loss)|publisher=My Deafness|accessdate=30 Nov 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=VEDA|title=VEDA-VEstibular Disorders Association-Ototoxicity|url=http://www.vestibular.org/vestibular-disorders/specific-disorders/ototoxicity.php|work=VEDA-Vestibular Disorders Association|publisher=VEDA|accessdate=30 Nov 2011}}</ref> although cochlear nerve terminal regeneration has been observed in chickens,<ref name=\"pmid9547237\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hennig AK, Cotanche DA | title = Regeneration of cochlear efferent nerve terminals after gentamycin damage | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 18 | issue = 9 | pages = 3282\u201396 | year = 1998 | pmid = 9547237 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.18-09-03282.1998| doi-access = free }}</ref> which suggests that there may be a way to accomplish this in humans.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|H|91|0|h|90}} \n|   ICD9           = \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = ent \n|   eMedicineTopic = 699 \n|   DiseasesDB     = 2874 \n}}\n* OSHA-NIOSH  2018. [https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-124/pdfs/2018-124.pdf Preventing Hearing Loss Caused by Chemical (Ototoxicity) and Noise Exposure Safety and Health Information Bulletin (SHIB)], Occupational Safety and Health Administration and the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.  SHIB 03-08-2018. DHHS (NIOSH) Publication No. 2018-124. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.26616/NIOSHPUB2018124</nowiki>\n*[https://synergist.aiha.org/201811-the-ear-poisons The Ear Poisons], The Synergist, [[American Industrial Hygiene Association]], 2018.\n\n{{Diseases of the ear and mastoid process}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Occupational safety and health}}\n[[Category:Hearing loss]]\n[[Category:Ototoxicity]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Ototoxicity \n| image           =  \n| caption         =  \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           = [[Otorhinolaryngology]]\n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Ototoxicity''' is the <!-- changed from 'quality' to property (hardly a quality) -->property of being [[toxicity|toxic]] to the [[ear]] (''oto-''), specifically the [[cochlea]] or [[vestibulocochlear nerve|auditory nerve]] and sometimes the [[vestibular system]], for example, as a side effect of a drug. The effects of ototoxicity can be reversible and temporary, or irreversible and permanent. \nIt has been recognized since the 19th century.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schacht J, Hawkins JE | title = Sketches of otohistory. Part 11: Ototoxicity: drug-induced hearing loss | journal = Audiology and Neuro-Otology | volume = 11 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u20136 | date = 2006-01-01 | pmid = 16219991 | doi = 10.1159/000088850 }}</ref> \nThere are many well-known ototoxic drugs used in clinical situations, and they are prescribed, despite the risk of hearing disorders, to very serious health conditions.<ref>{{cite book | url = http://audiology-web.s3.amazonaws.com/migrated/OtoMonGuidelines.pdf_539974c40999c1.58842217.pdf | title = Position Statement and Practice Guidelines on Ototoxicity Monitoring | publisher = American Academy of Audiology | year = 2009 }}</ref> \nOtotoxic drugs include [[antibiotic]]s such as [[gentamicin]], [[streptomycin]], [[tobramycin]], [[loop diuretic]]s such as [[furosemide]] and [[platinum]]-based [[chemotherapy]] agents such as [[cisplatin]], [[carboplatin]], and [[vincristine]]. A number of [[nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug]]s (NSAIDS) have also been shown to be ototoxic.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cazals Y | title = Auditory sensori-neural alterations induced by salicylate | journal = Progress in Neurobiology | volume = 62 | issue = 6 | pages = 583\u2013631 | date = December 2000 | pmid = 10880852 | doi = 10.1016/s0301-0082(00)00027-7 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jung|first=T. T.|last2=Rhee|first2=C. K.|last3=Lee|first3=C. S.|last4=Park|first4=Y. S.|last5=Choi|first5=D. C.|date=October 1993|title=Ototoxicity of salicylate, nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drugs, and quinine|journal=Otolaryngologic Clinics of North America|volume=26|issue=5|pages=791\u2013810|issn=0030-6665|pmid=8233489}}</ref> This can result in [[sensorineural hearing loss]], [[dysequilibrium]], or both. Some environmental and occupational chemicals have also been shown to affect the [[auditory system]] and interact with noise.<ref name=\"Johnson_2010\">{{cite journal| vauthors = Johnson AC, Morata TC | date = 2010 | title = Occupational exposure to chemicals and hearing impairment. The Nordic Expert Group for Criteria Documentation of Health Risks from Chemicals | url = https://gupea.ub.gu.se/bitstream/2077/23240/1/gupea_2077_23240_1.pdf | journal = Arbete och H\u00e4lsa |volume=44 |issue=4 |pages=177|doi=|pmid=|access-date=May 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nSymptoms of ototoxicity include partial or profound [[Hearing impairment|hearing loss]], [[Vertigo (medical)|vertigo]], and [[tinnitus]].<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\nThe cochlea is primarily a hearing structure situated in the inner ear. It is the snail-shaped shell containing several nerve endings that makes hearing possible.<ref name=Farlex>{{cite web|url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/ototoxicity|work=The Free Dictionary by Farlex|title=ototoxicity}}</ref>\nOtotoxicity typically results when the inner ear is poisoned by medication that damages the cochlea, vestibule, semi-circular canals, or the auditory/ vestibulocochlear nerve. The damaged structure then produces the symptoms the patient presents with. Ototoxicity in the cochlea may cause hearing loss of the high-frequency pitch ranges or complete deafness, or losses at points between.<ref name=Mudd>{{cite web|last=Mudd|first=Pamela | name-list-format = vanc |title=Ototoxicity|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/857679-overview|work=Medscape Reference|publisher=WebMD LLC|accessdate=30 Nov 2011}}</ref>  It may present with bilaterally symmetrical symptoms, or asymmetrically, with one ear developing the condition after the other or not at all.<ref name=Mudd/> The time frames for progress of the disease vary greatly and symptoms of hearing loss may be temporary or permanent.<ref name=Farlex/>\n\nThe [[vestibule of the ear|vestibule]] and [[semi-circular canal]] are inner-ear components that comprise the vestibular system. Together they detect all directions of head movement. Two types of [[otolith organs]] are housed in the vestibule: the [[saccule]], which points vertically and detects vertical acceleration, and the [[utricle (ear)|utricle]], which points horizontally and detects horizontal acceleration. The otolith organs together sense the head's position with respect to gravity when the body is static; then the head's movement when it tilts; and pitch changes during any linear motion of the head. The saccule and utricle detect different motions, which information the brain receives and integrates to determine where the head is and how and where it is moving.\n\nThe semi-circular canals are three bony structures filled with fluid. As with the vestibule, the primary purpose of the canals is to detect movement. Each canal is oriented at right angles to the others, enabling detection of movement in any plane. The posterior canal detects rolling motion, or motion about the X axis; the anterior canal detects pitch, or motion about the Y axis; the horizontal canal detects yaw motion, or motion about the Z axis. \nWhen a medication is toxic in the vestibule or the semi-circular canals, the patient senses loss of balance or orientation rather than losses in hearing. Symptoms in these organs present as vertigo, difficulties walking in low light and darkness, disequilibrium, oscillopsia among others.<ref name=Mudd/> Each of these problems is related to balance and the mind is confused with the direction of motion or lack of motion. Both the vestibule and semi-circular canals transmit information to the brain about movement; when these are poisoned, they are unable to function properly which results in miscommunication with the brain.\n\nWhen the vestibule and/or semi-circular canals are affected by ototoxicity, the eye can also be affected. [[Nystagmus]] and [[oscillopsia]] are two conditions that overlap the vestibular and ocular systems. These symptoms cause the patient to have difficulties with seeing and processing images. The body subconsciously tries to compensate for the imbalance signals being sent to the brain by trying to obtain visual cues to support the information it is receiving. This results in that dizziness and \"woozy\" feeling patients use to describe conditions such as oscillopsia and vertigo.<ref name=Mudd/>\n\n[[Cranial nerve VIII]] is the least affected component of the ear when ototoxicity arises, but if the nerve is affected, the damage is most often permanent. Symptoms present similar to those resulting from vestibular and cochlear damage, including tinnitus, ringing of the ears, difficulty walking, deafness, and balance and orientation issues.\n\n==Ototoxic agents==\n\n===Antibiotics===\nAntibiotics in the [[aminoglycoside]] class, such as [[gentamicin]] and [[tobramycin]], may produce cochleotoxicity through a poorly understood mechanism.<ref name=\"pmid16549744\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dobie RA, Black FO, Pezsnecker SC, Stallings VL | title = Hearing loss in patients with vestibulotoxic reactions to gentamicin therapy | journal = Archives of Otolaryngology\u2013Head & Neck Surgery | volume = 132 | issue = 3 | pages = 253\u20137 | date = March 2006 | pmid = 16549744 | doi = 10.1001/archotol.132.3.253 | doi-access = free }}</ref> It may result from antibiotic binding to [[NMDA receptor]]s in the [[cochlea]] and damaging [[neuron]]s through [[excitotoxicity]].<ref name=\"pmid8946832\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Basile AS, Huang JM, Xie C, Webster D, Berlin C, Skolnick P | title = N-methyl-D-aspartate antagonists limit aminoglycoside antibiotic-induced hearing loss | journal = Nature Medicine | volume = 2 | issue = 12 | pages = 1338\u201343 | date = December 1996 | pmid = 8946832 | doi = 10.1038/nm1296-1338 }}</ref> Aminoglycoside-induced production of [[reactive oxygen species]] may also injure cells of the [[cochlea]].<ref name=\"pmid12053140\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wu WJ, Sha SH, Schacht J | title = Recent advances in understanding aminoglycoside ototoxicity and its prevention | journal = Audiology and Neuro-Otology | volume = 7 | issue = 3 | pages = 171\u20134 | year = 2002 | pmid = 12053140 | doi = 10.1159/000058305 }}</ref> Once-daily dosing<ref name=\"pmid8722531\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Munckhof WJ, Grayson ML, Turnidge JD | title = A meta-analysis of studies on the safety and efficacy of aminoglycosides given either once daily or as divided doses | journal = The Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy | volume = 37 | issue = 4 | pages = 645\u201363 | date = April 1996 | pmid = 8722531 | doi = 10.1093/jac/37.4.645 | doi-access = free }}</ref> and co-administration of [[N-acetylcysteine|''N''-acetylcysteine]]<ref name=\"pmid17653228\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tepel M | title = N-Acetylcysteine in the prevention of ototoxicity | journal = Kidney International | volume = 72 | issue = 3 | pages = 231\u20132 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17653228 | doi = 10.1038/sj.ki.5002299 }}</ref> may protect against aminoglycoside-induced ototoxicity. The anti-bacterial activity of aminoglycoside compounds is due to inhibition of ribosome function and these compounds similarly inhibit protein synthesis by mitochondrial ribosomes because mitochondria evolved from a bacterial ancestor.<ref name=\"pmid17116475\">{{Cite book | vauthors = Wirmer J, Westhof E | title = Molecular contacts between antibiotics and the 30S ribosomal particle | journal = Methods in Enzymology | volume = 415 | pages = 180\u2013202 | date = 2006 | pmid = 17116475 | doi = 10.1016/S0076-6879(06)15012-0 | isbn = 9780121828202 }}</ref> Consequently, aminoglycoside effects on production of reactive oxygen species as well as dysregulation of cellular calcium ion homeostasis may result from disruption of mitochondrial function.<ref name=\"pmid23616556\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Esterberg R, Hailey DW, Coffin AB, Raible DW, Rubel EW | title = Disruption of intracellular calcium regulation is integral to aminoglycoside-induced hair cell death | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 33 | issue = 17 | pages = 7513\u201325 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23616556 | pmc = 3703319 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4559-12.2013 }}</ref> Ototoxicity of gentamicin can be exploited to treat some individuals with [[M\u00e9ni\u00e8re's disease]] by destroying the inner ear,  which stops the vertigo attacks but causes permanent deafness.<ref name=\"pmid12616197\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Perez N, Mart\u00edn E, Garc\u00eda-Tapia R | title = Intratympanic gentamicin for intractable Meniere's disease | journal = The Laryngoscope | volume = 113 | issue = 3 | pages = 456\u201364 | date = March 2003 | pmid = 12616197 | doi = 10.1097/00005537-200303000-00013 }}</ref>\nDue to the effects on mitochondria, certain inherited mitochondrial disorders result in increased sensitivity to the toxic effects of aminoglycosides.\n\n[[Macrolide]] antibiotics, including [[erythromycin]], are associated with reversible ototoxic effects.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> The underlying mechanism of ototoxicity may be impairment of [[ion transport]] in the [[stria vascularis]].<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> Predisposing factors include [[renal impairment]], [[hepatic impairment]], and recent [[organ transplantation]].<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\n===Loop diuretics===\nCertain types of diuretics are associated with varying levels of risk for ototoxicity. Loop and thiazide diuretics carry this side effect. The [[loop diuretic]] [[furosemide]] is associated with ototoxicity, particularly when doses exceed 240&nbsp;mg per hour.<ref name=\"pmid3430953\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Voelker JR, Cartwright-Brown D, Anderson S, Leinfelder J, Sica DA, Kokko JP, Brater DC | title = Comparison of loop diuretics in patients with chronic renal insufficiency | journal = Kidney International | volume = 32 | issue = 4 | pages = 572\u20138 | date = October 1987 | pmid = 3430953 | doi = 10.1038/ki.1987.246 }}</ref> The related compound [[ethacrynic acid]] has a higher association with ototoxicity, and is therefore used only in patients with sulfa allergies. Diuretics are thought to alter the ionic gradient within the [[Stria vascularis of cochlear duct|stria vascularis]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Schmitz | first1 = Paul G. | name-list-format = vanc | title = Renal: An Integrated Approach to Disease | date = 2012 | publisher = McGraw-Hill | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-07-162155-7 | page = 123 }}</ref> [[Bumetanide]] confers a decreased risk of ototoxicity compared to furosemide.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\">{{cite book | last = Roland | first = Peter S. | name-list-format = vanc | title = Ototoxicity | publisher = B.C. Decker | location = Hamilton, Ont | year = 2004 |pages= |isbn=978-1-55009-263-9 }}</ref>\n\n===Chemotherapeutic agents===\n[[Platinum]]-containing chemotherapeutic agents, including [[cisplatin]] and [[carboplatin]], are associated with cochleotoxicity characterized by progressive, high-frequency hearing loss with or without [[tinnitus]] (ringing in the ears).<ref name=\"pmid16484702\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rademaker-Lakhai JM, Crul M, Zuur L, Baas P, Beijnen JH, Simis YJ, van Zandwijk N, Schellens JH | title = Relationship between cisplatin administration and the development of ototoxicity | journal = Journal of Clinical Oncology | volume = 24 | issue = 6 | pages = 918\u201324 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16484702 | doi = 10.1200/JCO.2006.10.077 }}</ref> Ototoxicity is less frequently seen with the related compound [[oxaliplatin]].<ref name=\"pmid19116379\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hellberg V, Wallin I, Eriksson S, Hernlund E, Jerremalm E, Berndtsson M, Eksborg S, Arn\u00e9r ES, Shoshan M, Ehrsson H, Laurell G | title = Cisplatin and oxaliplatin toxicity: importance of cochlear kinetics as a determinant for ototoxicity | journal = Journal of the National Cancer Institute | volume = 101 | issue = 1 | pages = 37\u201347 | date = January 2009 | pmid = 19116379 | pmc = 2639295 | doi = 10.1093/jnci/djn418 }}</ref> The severity of cisplatin-induced ototoxicity is dependent upon the cumulative dose administered<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bokemeyer C, Berger CC, Hartmann JT, Kollmannsberger C, Schmoll HJ, Kuczyk MA, Kanz L | title = Analysis of risk factors for cisplatin-induced ototoxicity in patients with testicular cancer | journal = British Journal of Cancer | volume = 77 | issue = 8 | pages = 1355\u201362 | date = April 1998 | pmid = 9579846 | pmc = 2150148  | doi = 10.1038/bjc.1998.226 }}</ref> and the age of the patient, with young children being most susceptible.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Li Y, Womer RB, Silber JH | title = Predicting cisplatin ototoxicity in children: the influence of age and the cumulative dose | journal = European Journal of Cancer | volume = 40 | issue = 16 | pages = 2445\u201351 | date = November 2004 | pmid = 15519518 | doi = 10.1016/j.ejca.2003.08.009  }}</ref> The exact mechanism of cisplatin ototoxicity is not known. The drug is understood to damage multiple regions of the cochlea, causing the death of outer [[hair cell]]s, as well as damage to the [[spiral ganglion]] neurons and cells of the [[Stria vascularis of cochlear duct|stria vascularis]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Callejo A, Sed\u00f3-Cabez\u00f3n L, Juan ID, Llorens J | title = Cisplatin-Induced Ototoxicity: Effects, Mechanisms and Protection Strategies | journal = Toxics | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 268\u2013293 | date = July 2015 | pmid = 29051464 | pmc = 5606684 | doi = 10.3390/toxics3030268 }}</ref> Long-term retention of cisplatin in the cochlea may contribute to the drug's cochleotoxic potential.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Breglio AM, Rusheen AE, Shide ED, Fernandez KA, Spielbauer KK, McLachlin KM, Hall MD, Amable L, Cunningham LL | title = Cisplatin is retained in the cochlea indefinitely following chemotherapy | journal = Nature Communications | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 1654 | date = November 2017 | pmid = 29162831 | pmc = 5698400 | doi = 10.1038/s41467-017-01837-1 }}</ref> Once inside the cochlea, cisplatin has been proposed to cause cellular toxicity through a number of different mechanisms, including through the production of [[reactive oxygen species]].<ref name=\"pmid17113254\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rybak LP, Whitworth CA, Mukherjea D, Ramkumar V | title = Mechanisms of cisplatin-induced ototoxicity and prevention | journal = Hearing Research | volume = 226 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 157\u201367 | date = April 2007 | pmid = 17113254 | doi = 10.1016/j.heares.2006.09.015 }}</ref> The decreased incidence of oxaliplatin ototoxicity has been attributed to decreased uptake of the drug by cells of the cochlea.<ref name=\"pmid19116379\"/> Administration of [[amifostine]] has been used in attempts to prevent cisplatin-induced ototoxicity, but the [[American Society of Clinical Oncology]] recommends against its routine use.<ref name=\"pmid19018081\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hensley ML, Hagerty KL, Kewalramani T, Green DM, Meropol NJ, Wasserman TH, Cohen GI, Emami B, Gradishar WJ, Mitchell RB, Thigpen JT, Trotti A, von Hoff D, Schuchter LM | title = American Society of Clinical Oncology 2008 clinical practice guideline update: use of chemotherapy and radiation therapy protectants | journal = Journal of Clinical Oncology | volume = 27 | issue = 1 | pages = 127\u201345 | date = January 2009 | pmid = 19018081 | doi = 10.1200/JCO.2008.17.2627 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[vinca alkaloid|''vinca'' alkaloids]],<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = van Der Heijden R, Jacobs DI, Snoeijer W, Hallard D, Verpoorte R | title = The Catharanthus alkaloids: pharmacognosy and biotechnology | journal = Current Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 11 | issue = 5 | pages = 607\u201328 | date = March 2004 | pmid = 15032608 | doi = 10.2174/0929867043455846 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last = Ravi\u00f1a|first = Enrique | name-list-format = vanc |title = The evolution of drug discovery: From traditional medicines to modern drugs|year = 2011|publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons]] | isbn = 978-3-527-32669-3 | pages = 157\u2013159|chapter = Vinca alkaloids|chapter-url = https://books.google.ca/books?id=iDNy0XxGqT8C&pg=PA157}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter = Africa's gift to the world|pages = 46\u201351|chapter-url = https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aXGmCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46|title = Botanical Miracles: Chemistry of Plants That Changed the World|first1 = Raymond|last1 = Cooper|first2 = Jeffrey John|last2 = Deakin | name-list-format = vanc |publisher = [[CRC Press]]|year = 2016 | isbn = 978-1-4987-0430-4 }}</ref> including [[vincristine]],<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Keglevich P, Hazai L, Kalaus G, Sz\u00e1ntay C | title = Modifications on the basic skeletons of vinblastine and vincristine | journal = Molecules | volume = 17 | issue = 5 | pages = 5893\u2013914 | date = May 2012 | pmid = 22609781 | pmc = 6268133 | doi = 10.3390/molecules17055893 }}</ref> are also associated with reversible ototoxicity.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\n===Antiseptics and disinfectants===\n\nTopical skin preparations such as [[chlorhexidine]] and [[ethyl alcohol]] have the potential to be ototoxic should they enter the inner ear through the [[round window membrane]].<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> This potential was first noted after a small percentage of patients undergoing early [[myringoplasty]] operations experienced severe sensorineural hearing loss. It was found that in all operations involving this complication the preoperative sterilization was done with chlorhexidine.<ref>{{cite journal  |author=Bicknell, P. G. |title=Sensorineural deafness following myringoplasty operations |journal=The Journal of Laryngology & Otology |volume=85 |issue=9 |pages=957\u2013962 |date=1971 |doi=10.1017/S0022215100074272   }}</ref> The ototoxicity of chlorhexidine was further confirmed by studies with animal models.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\nSeveral other skin preparations have been shown to be potentially ototoxic in the animal model. These preparations include [[acetic acid]], [[propylene glycol]], [[quaternary ammonium compounds]], and any alcohol-based preparations. However, it is difficult to extrapolate these results to human ototoxicity because the human round window membrane is much thicker than in any animal model.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/>\n\n===Other medicinal ototoxic drugs===\nAt high doses, quinine, [[aspirin]] and other [[salicylate]]s may also cause high-pitch [[tinnitus]] and hearing loss in both ears, typically reversible upon discontinuation of the drug.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> Erectile dysfunction medications may have the potential to cause hearing loss.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/2007/ucm109012.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090709212332/https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/2007/ucm109012.htm | url-status = dead | archive-date = 9 July 2009 | title = FDA Announces Revisions to Labels for Cialis, Levitra and Viagra. Potential risk of sudden hearing loss with ED drugs to be displayed more prominently | publisher = United States Food and Drug Administration }}</ref> However the link between erectile dysfunction medications and hearing loss remains uncertain.<ref name=\"pmid28923561\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Yafi FA, Sharlip ID, Becher EF | title = Update on the Safety of Phosphodiesterase Type 5 Inhibitors for the Treatment of Erectile Dysfunction | journal = Sexual Medicine Reviews | volume = 6| issue = 2| pages = 242\u2013252| year = 2017 | pmid = 28923561 | doi = 10.1016/j.sxmr.2017.08.001 }}</ref>\n\nPrevious noise exposure has not been found to potentiate ototoxic hearing loss.<ref name=\"Campbell_2007\" /><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Laurell G, Borg E|date=1986-01-01|title=Cis-platin ototoxicity in previously noise-exposed guinea pigs|journal=Acta Oto-Laryngologica|volume=101|issue=1\u20132|pages=66\u201374|doi=10.3109/00016488609108609|pmid=3962651}}</ref> The American Academy of Audiology includes in their position statement that exposure to noise at the same time as [[aminoglycoside]]s may exacerbate ototoxicity. The American Academy of Audiology recommends people being treated with ototoxic chemotherapeutics avoid excessive noise levels during treatment and for several months following cessation of treatment. Opiates in combination with excessive noise levels may also have an additive effect on ototoxic hearing loss.<ref>{{cite book|title=Hearing Conservation in Occupational, Recreational, Educational, and Home Settings|last=Rawool|first=Vishakha Waman|publisher=Thieme|year=2012|isbn=978-1-60406-256-4|location=New York|pages=13|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref>\n\n=== Ototoxicants in the environment and workplace ===\nOtotoxic effects are also seen with [[quinine]], [[pesticide]]s, [[solvent]]s, [[Asphyxiant gas|asphyxiants]], and [[Heavy metal (chemistry)|heavy metal]]s such as [[mercury (element)|mercury]] and [[lead]].<ref name=\"Johnson_2010\" /><ref name=\"ototoxicity\" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Campo P, Morata TC, Hong O | title = Chemical exposure and hearing loss | journal = Disease-A-Month | volume = 59 | issue = 4 | pages = 119\u201338 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23507352 | pmc = 4693596 | doi = 10.1016/j.disamonth.2013.01.003 }}</ref> When combining multiple ototoxicants, the risk of hearing loss becomes greater.<ref>{{cite book | title = Hearing Conservation: In Occupational, Recreational, Educational, and Home settings | last = Rawool | first = Vishakha | name-list-format = vanc | publisher = Thieme | year = 2012 | location = New York, NY | pages = 10 | isbn = 978-1-60406-256-4 }}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Venet|first=Thomas|last2=Carreres-Pons|first2=Maria|last3=Chalansonnet|first3=Monique|last4=Thomas|first4=Aur\u00e9lie|last5=Merlen|first5=Lise|last6=Nunge|first6=Herv\u00e9|last7=Bonfanti|first7=Elodie|last8=Cosnier|first8=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last9=Llorens|first9=Jordi|date=2017-09-01|title=Continuous exposure to low-frequency noise and carbon disulfide: Combined effects on hearing|journal=NeuroToxicology|volume=62|pages=151\u2013161|doi=10.1016/j.neuro.2017.06.013|pmid=28655499|issn=0161-813X}}</ref> As these exposures are common, this hearing impairment can affect many occupations and industries.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Nordic Expert Group for criteria documentation of health risks from chemicals. 142, Occupational exposure to chemicals and hearing impairment|last=1955-|first=Johnson, Ann-Christin|date=2009|publisher=University of Gothenburg|others=Morata, Thais C.|isbn=9789185971213|location=G\u00f6teborg|oclc=939229378}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lewkowski|first=Kate|last2=Heyworth|first2=Jane S.|last3=Li|first3=Ian W.|last4=Williams|first4=Warwick|last5=McCausland|first5=Kahlia|last6=Gray|first6=Corie|last7=Ytterstad|first7=Elinor|last8=Glass|first8=Deborah C.|last9=Fuente|first9=Adrian|last10=Si|first10=Si|last11=Florath|first11=Ines|date=2019|title=Exposure to noise and ototoxic chemicals in the Australian workforce|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30683670|journal=Occupational and Environmental Medicine|volume=76|issue=5|pages=341\u2013348|doi=10.1136/oemed-2018-105471|issn=1470-7926|pmid=30683670|via=}}</ref>  Examples of activities that often have exposures to both noise and solvents include<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osha.gov/dts/shib/shib030818.html|title=Safety and Health Information Bulletins {{!}} Preventing Hearing Loss Caused by Chemical (Ototoxicity) and Noise Exposure {{!}} Occupational Safety and Health Administration|website=www.osha.gov|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>: \n\n* Printing\n* Painting\n* Construction\n* Fueling vehicles and aircrafts\n* Firefighting\n* Weapons firing\n* Pesticide spraying\n\nOtotoxic chemicals in the environment (from contaminated air or water) or in the workplace interact with mechanical stresses on the hair cells of the cochlea in different ways. For mixtures containing organic solvents such as [[toluene]], [[styrene]] or [[xylene]], the combined exposure with noise increases the risk of occupational [[Occupational hearing loss|hearing loss]] in a [[synergy|synergistic]] manner.<ref name=\"Johnson_2010\" /><ref name=\"Fechter_2004\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fechter LD | title = Promotion of noise-induced hearing loss by chemical contaminants | journal = Journal of Toxicology and Environmental Health. Part A | volume = 67 | issue = 8\u201310 | pages = 727\u201340 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15192865 | doi = 10.1080/15287390490428206 }}</ref> The risk is greatest when the co-exposure is with impulse noise.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Venet|first=Thomas|last2=Campo|first2=Pierre|last3=Thomas|first3=Aur\u00e9lie|last4=Cour|first4=Chantal|last5=Rieger|first5=Beno\u00eet|last6=Cosnier|first6=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|title=The tonotopicity of styrene-induced hearing loss depends on the associated noise spectrum|journal=Neurotoxicology and Teratology|volume=48|pages=56\u201363|doi=10.1016/j.ntt.2015.02.003|pmid=25689156|year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fuente|first=Adrian|last2=Qiu|first2=Wei|last3=Zhang|first3=Meibian|last4=Xie|first4=Hongwei|last5=Kardous|first5=Chucri A.|last6=Campo|first6=Pierre|last7=Morata|first7=Thais C.|date=March 2018|title=Use of the kurtosis statistic in an evaluation of the effects of noise and solvent exposures on the hearing thresholds of workers: An exploratory study|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=143|issue=3|pages=1704|doi=10.1121/1.5028368|issn=1520-8524|pmid=29604694|url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01844639/file/10.1121_1.5028368.pdf}}</ref> [[Carbon monoxide]] has been shown to increase the severity of the hearing loss from noise.<ref name=\"Fechter_2004\" /> Given the potential for enhanced risk of hearing loss, exposures and contact with products such as fuels, paint thinners, degreasers, white spirits, exhaust, should be kept to a minimum.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2018-03-01|title=Preventing hearing loss caused by chemical (ototoxicity) and noise exposure.|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-124/|language=en|doi=10.26616/nioshpub2018124|doi-access=free}}</ref> Noise exposures should be kept below 85 decibels, and the chemical exposures should be below the recommended exposure limits given by regulatory agencies.\n\nDrug exposures mixed with noise potentially lead to increased risk of ototoxic hearing loss. Noise exposure combined with the chemotherapeutic [[cisplatin]] puts individuals at increased risk of ototoxic hearing loss.<ref name=\"Campbell_2007\">{{cite book | title = Pharmacology and Ototoxicity for Audiologists | last = Campbell | first = Kathleen | name-list-format = vanc | publisher = Delmar Centrage Learning | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-1-4180-1130-7 | location = Clifton Park, NY | pages = 145 }}</ref> Noise at 85&nbsp;dB SPL or above added to the amount of hair cell death in the high frequency region of the cochlea in chinchillas.<ref name=\"pmid2076973\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gratton MA, Salvi RJ, Kamen BA, Saunders SS | title = Interaction of cisplatin and noise on the peripheral auditory system | journal = Hearing Research | volume = 50 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 211\u201323 | year = 1990 | pmid = 2076973 | doi = 10.1016/0378-5955(90)90046-R }}</ref>\n\nThe hearing loss caused by chemicals can be very similar to a hearing loss caused by excessive noise.  A 2018 informational bulletin by the US [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration]] (OSHA) and the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] (NIOSH) introduces the issue, provides examples of ototoxic chemicals, lists the industries and occupations at risk and provides prevention information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-124/pdfs/2018-124.pdf|title=Preventing Hearing Loss Caused by Chemical (Ototoxicity) and Noise Exposure|last=Occupational Safety and Health Administration|first=National Institute for Occupational Safety and Heath|date=April 3, 2018|website=OSHA, NIOSH|archive-url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-124/pdfs/2018-124.pdf|archive-date=March 2018|url-status=|access-date=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Treatment==\nNo specific treatment may be available, but withdrawal of the ototoxic drug may be warranted when the consequences of doing so are less severe than those of the ototoxicity.<ref name=\"ototoxicity\"/> Co-administration of anti-oxidants may limit the ototoxic effects.<ref name=\"Campbell_2007\" />\n\nOtotoxic monitoring during exposure is recommended by the American Academy of Audiology to allow for proper detection and possible prevention or rehabilitation of the hearing loss through a [[cochlear implant]] or [[hearing aid]]. Monitoring can be completed through performing [[otoacoustic emission]]s testing or high frequency [[audiometry]]. Successful monitoring includes a baseline test before, or soon after, exposure to the ototoxicant. Follow-up testing is completed in increments after the first exposure, throughout the cessation of treatment. Shifts in hearing status are monitored and relayed to the prescribing physician to make treatment decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://audiology-web.s3.amazonaws.com/migrated/OtoMonGuidelines.pdf_539974c40999c1.58842217.pdf|title=American Academy of Audiology Position Statement and Clinical Practice Guidelines: Ototoxic Monitoring | last = Durrant | first = John | name-list-format = vanc |date=October 2009 |website=American Academy of Audiology|publisher=American Academy of Audiology |access-date = 4 December 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIt is difficult to distinguish between nerve damage and structural damage due to similarity of the symptoms.  Diagnosis of ototoxicity typically results from ruling out all other possible sources of hearing loss and is often the catchall explanation for the symptoms. Treatment options vary depending on the patient and the diagnosis. Some patients experience only temporary symptoms that do not require drastic treatment while others can be treated with medication. Physical therapy may prove useful for regaining balance and walking abilities. [[Cochlear implant]]s are sometimes an option to restore hearing. Such treatments are typically taken to comfort the patient, not to cure the disease or damage caused by ototoxicity. There is no cure or restoration capability if the damage becomes permanent,<ref>{{cite web|last=My Deafness|title=Ototoxicity: Ear Poisoning|url=http://www.mydeafness.com/ototoxicity-ear-poisoning|work=Causes of Deafness and Types of Deafness (Hearing Loss)|publisher=My Deafness|accessdate=30 Nov 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=VEDA|title=VEDA-VEstibular Disorders Association-Ototoxicity|url=http://www.vestibular.org/vestibular-disorders/specific-disorders/ototoxicity.php|work=VEDA-Vestibular Disorders Association|publisher=VEDA|accessdate=30 Nov 2011}}</ref> although cochlear nerve terminal regeneration has been observed in chickens,<ref name=\"pmid9547237\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hennig AK, Cotanche DA | title = Regeneration of cochlear efferent nerve terminals after gentamycin damage | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 18 | issue = 9 | pages = 3282\u201396 | year = 1998 | pmid = 9547237 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.18-09-03282.1998| doi-access = free }}</ref> which suggests that there may be a way to accomplish this in humans.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|H|91|0|h|90}} \n|   ICD9           = \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = ent \n|   eMedicineTopic = 699 \n|   DiseasesDB     = 2874 \n}}\n* OSHA-NIOSH  2018. [https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-124/pdfs/2018-124.pdf Preventing Hearing Loss Caused by Chemical (Ototoxicity) and Noise Exposure Safety and Health Information Bulletin (SHIB)], Occupational Safety and Health Administration and the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.  SHIB 03-08-2018. DHHS (NIOSH) Publication No. 2018-124. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.26616/NIOSHPUB2018124</nowiki>\n*[https://synergist.aiha.org/201811-the-ear-poisons The Ear Poisons], The Synergist, [[American Industrial Hygiene Association]], 2018.\n\n{{Diseases of the ear and mastoid process}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Occupational safety and health}}\n[[Category:Hearing loss]]\n[[Category:Ototoxicity]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ototoxicity"}
{"title_page": "Hichem Rostom", "text_new": "{{short description|Tunisian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =Hichem Rostom 03.JPG\n| caption = Hichem Rostom in 2015.\n| name         = Hichem Rostom\n| native_name       = \u0647\u0634\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0633\u062a\u0645\n| native_name_lang  = Arabic\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|5|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[La Marsa]], [[Tunisia]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Tunisian\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1987\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Hichem Rostom''' (born 26 May 1947) is a Tunisian actor of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Festival Tetouan|title=Hommages 2012: Hichem Rostom , Acteur Tunisien|url=http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|accessdate=18 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502142050/http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|archivedate=2 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has appeared in 28 films and television shows since 1987. He starred in ''[[Golden Horseshoes]]'', which was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival|1989 festival]].<ref name=\"cannes-1989.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/260/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Golden Horseshoes |accessdate=2 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> He also directed the Carthage Theatre Festival for two sessions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sharmfilmfest.com/index.php/festival/jury/132-hichem-rostom|title=Sharm El-Sheikh Arab & European Film Festival|last=admin|first=sharm|access-date=20 July 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n==Cinema==\n==Tunisian feature Films==\n* [[1988]] : ''[[The Golden Clogs]]'' by [[Nouri Bouzid]] : Si Youssef\n* [[1989]] : ''[[Layla, My Reason]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]] : The Husband of Layla\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Silence of The Palace]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]] : Mr Bacheer\n* [[1997]] : ''[[Essa\u00efda]]'' by [[Mohamed Zran]] : Ameen\n* [[1998]] : ''[[Moon Wedding]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]\n* [[1999]] : ''[[Grenadine Naps]]'' by [[Mahmoud Ben Mahmoud]] : Wahid Haydar\n* [[2002]] : ''[[The Magic Box]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]) : Mansour\n* [[2002]] : ''[[The Song of The noria]]'' by [[Abdellatif Ben Ammar]) : Ali\n* [[2003]] : ''[[The Murdered Sun]]'' by [[Abdelkrim Bahloul]] : Bramsi\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Nadia and Sarra]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]] : Hedy\n* [[2006]] : ''[[The Tv arrives]]'' by [[Moncef Dhouib]] : The Director\n* [[2014]] : ''[[The Child of The Sun]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]] : Kateb\n* [[2014]] : ''[[Zero !]] by [[Nidhal Chatta]]'' : The Father\n* [[2014]] : ''[[The Last mirage]]'' by [[Nidhal Chatta]] : Dr Oussama Saad\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Dicta Shot]]'' by [[Mokhtar Ladjimi]] : Mr Hazem\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Conflit]]'' by Moncef Barbouch9 : Mokhtar\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Alep's flower]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]] : The Father of Mourad\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Woh !]]'' by [[Ismahane Lahmar]] : Hmed\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Whispering Sands]] by [[Nacer Kh\u00e9mir]]\n\n==Foreign Feature Films==\n* [[1976]] : ''[[Wing or thigh]]'' by [[Claude Zidi]]\n* [[1982]] : ''[[Sandstorm]]''  by [[Mohammed Lakhdar-Hamina]]\n* [[1991]] : ''[[L'amico arabo]] (The Arab Friend) by [[Carmine Fornari]] (it)\n* [[1991]] : ''[[Isabelle Eberhardt]] by [[Ian Pringle]] (en)\n* [[1992]] : ''[[Indiscreet goals]]'' by [[Massimo Mazzuco]] : Manuel The Red\n* [[1993]] : ''[[The Navel of the World]]'' by [[Ariel Zeitoun]] : Costa\n* [[1997]] : ''[[The English Patient]]'' by [[Anthony Minghella]] : Fouad\n* [[1998]] : ''[[Paparazzi]]'' by [[Alain Berberian]] : El Kabouli\n* [[2001]] : ''[[The Desert and the Forest]] (pl) by [[Gavin Hood]] : Mahdi\n* [[2008]] : ''[[The Song of the Brides]] by [[Karin Albou]] : The Father of Raoul\n* [[2008]] : ''[[Whatever Lola Wants]] by [[Nabil Ayouch]] : Nacer\n* [[2011]] : ''[[The Fifth String]] by [[Selma Bergach]] : Amir\n* [[2011]] : ''[[Black Gold]]'' by [[Jean-Jacques Annaud]] : Colonel Nesibi\n\n==Short Films==\n* [[1989]] : ''[[The Trance]]'' by [[Moncef Dhouib]]\n\n==Dubbing==\n* [[2006]] : ''[[Azur and Asmar]]'' by [[Michel Ocelot]] (Dessins Anim\u00e9s)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|0744599|Hichem Rostom}}\n*{{Commons-inline|Category:Hichem Rostom|Hichem Rostom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rostom, Hichem}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Tunisian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tunisian male actors]]\n{{Tunisia-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tunisian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =Hichem Rostom 03.JPG\n| caption = Hichem Rostom in 2015.\n| name         = Hichem Rostom\n| native_name       = \u0647\u0634\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0633\u062a\u0645\n| native_name_lang  = Arabic\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|5|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[La Marsa]], [[Tunisia]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Tunisian\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1987\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Hichem Rostom''' (born 26 May 1947) is a Tunisian actor of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Festival Tetouan|title=Hommages 2012: Hichem Rostom , Acteur Tunisien|url=http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|accessdate=18 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502142050/http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|archivedate=2 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has appeared in 28 films and television shows since 1987. He starred in ''[[Golden Horseshoes]]'', which was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival|1989 festival]].<ref name=\"cannes-1989.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/260/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Golden Horseshoes |accessdate=2 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> He also directed the Carthage Theatre Festival for two sessions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sharmfilmfest.com/index.php/festival/jury/132-hichem-rostom|title=Sharm El-Sheikh Arab & European Film Festival|last=admin|first=sharm|access-date=20 July 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n==Cinema==\n==Tunisian feature Films==\n* [[1988]] : ''[[The Golden Clogs]]'' by [[Nouri Bouzid]] : Si Youssef\n* [[1989]] : ''[[Layla, My Reason]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]] : The Husband of Layla\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Silence of The Palace]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]] : Mr Bacheer\n* [[1997]] : ''[[Essa\u00efda]]'' by [[Mohamed Zran]] : Ameen\n* [[1998]] : ''[[Moon Wedding]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]\n* [[1999]] : ''[[Grenadine Naps]]'' by [[Mahmoud Ben Mahmoud]] : Wahid Haydar\n* [[2002]] : ''[[The Magic Box]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]) : Mansour\n* [[2002]] : ''[[The Song of The noria]]'' by [[Abdellatif Ben Ammar]) : Ali\n* [[2003]] : ''[[The Murdered Sun]]'' by [[Abdelkrim Bahloul]] : Bramsi\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Nadia and Sarra]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]] : Hedy\n* [[2006]] : ''[[The Tv arrives]]'' by [[Moncef Dhouib]] : The Director\n* [[2014]] : ''[[The Child of The Sun]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]] : Kateb\n* [[2014]] : ''[[Zero !]] by [[Nidhal Chatta]]'' : The Father\n* [[2014]] : ''[[The Last mirage]]'' by [[Nidhal Chatta]] : Dr Oussama Saad\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Dicta Shot]]'' by [[Mokhtar Ladjimi]] : Mr Hazem\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Conflit]]'' by Moncef Barbouch9 : Mokhtar\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Alep's flower]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]] : The Father of Mourad\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Woh !]]'' by [[Ismahane Lahmar]] : Hmed\n* [[2016]] : ''[[Whispering Sands]] by [[Nacer Kh\u00e9mir]]\n\n==Longs m\u00e9trages \u00e9trangers==\n* [[1976]] : ''[[Wing or thigh]]'' by [[Claude Zidi]]\n* [[1982]] : ''[[Sandstorm]]''  by [[Mohammed Lakhdar-Hamina]]\n* [[1991]] : ''[[L'amico arabo]] (The Arab Friend) by [[Carmine Fornari]] (it)\n* [[1991]] : ''[[Isabelle Eberhardt]] by [[Ian Pringle]] (en)\n* [[1992]] : ''[[Indiscreet goals]]'' by [[Massimo Mazzuco]] : Manuel The Red\n* [[1993]] : ''[[The Navel of the World]]'' by [[Ariel Zeitoun]] : Costa\n* [[1997]] : ''[[The English Patient]]'' by [[Anthony Minghella]] : Fouad\n* [[1998]] : ''[[Paparazzi]]'' by [[Alain Berberian]] : El Kabouli\n* [[2001]] : ''[[The Desert and the Forest]] (pl) by [[Gavin Hood]] : Mahdi\n* [[2008]] : ''[[The Song of the Brides]] by [[Karin Albou]] : The Father of Raoul\n* [[2008]] : ''[[Whatever Lola Wants]] by [[Nabil Ayouch]] : Nacer\n* [[2011]] : ''[[The Fifth String]] by [[Selma Bergach]] : Amir\n* [[2011]] : ''[[Black Gold]]'' by [[Jean-Jacques Annaud]] : Colonel Nesibi\n\n==Short Films==\n* [[1989]] : ''[[The Trance]]'' by [[Moncef Dhouib]]\n\n==Dubbing==\n* [[2006]] : ''[[Azur and Asmar]]'' by [[Michel Ocelot]] (Dessins Anim\u00e9s)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|0744599|Hichem Rostom}}\n*{{Commons-inline|Category:Hichem Rostom|Hichem Rostom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rostom, Hichem}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Tunisian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tunisian male actors]]\n{{Tunisia-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nesrine1984", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLongs m\u00e9trages \u00e9trangers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hichem_Rostom"}
{"title_page": "ZZ Top", "text_new": "{{short description|American rock band}}\n{{use mdy dates |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = ZZ Top\n|image           = ZZ Top on the Pyramid Stage at Glastonbury 2016 IMG 8527 (27374417884).jpg\n|image_size      = 350\n|caption         = ZZ Top (from left: [[Dusty Hill]], [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]], [[Billy Gibbons]]) at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] in June 2016\n|landscape       = yes\n|background      = group_or_band\n|origin          = [[Houston]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n|genre           = {{hlist|[[Blues rock]]<ref>{{cite web|first= Cub |last= Koda |title= ZZ Top \u2013 Artist Biography |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/zz-top-mn0000690254/biography |publisher= [[AllMusic]]. [[All Media Network]] |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-first= Patricia |editor-last= Bashe |editor-first2= Holly |editor-last2= George-Warren |year= 2001 |title= The Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll |url= https://archive.org/details/rollingstoneency00holl |edition= 3rd |publisher= [[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn= 978-0-7432-0120-9 |url-access= registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= Nick |last= Talevski |title= Rock Obituaries \u2013 Knocking On Heaven's Door |publisher= [[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]] |year= 2006 |page= 173 |isbn= 978-1-8460-9091-2}}</ref>|[[boogie rock]]<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Fred |last= Bonson |title= Wea's Greatest Hits |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume= 108 |issue= 35 |date= August 31, 1996 |page= 34 |quote= It was the band's second album, \"Tres Hombres,\" that established their boogie-rock credentials by peaking at No. 8 in 1974. |issn= 0006-2510}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= Matt |last= Cibula |url= http://www.popmatters.com/review/zztop-mescalero/ |title= ZZ Top: Mescalero |work= [[PopMatters]] |date= January 4, 2004 |accessdate= February 20, 2014}}</ref>|[[hard rock]]<ref>{{cite book|title= If You Like Metallica... |first= Mike |last= McPadden |year= 2012 |publisher= [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Backbeat Books]] |chapter= ZZ Top |chapter-url= https://books.google.com/?id=9o978TWC1hAC&pg=PT30 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= Ronald |last= Zalkind |title= Contemporary Music Almanac: 1980\u20131981 |publisher= [[G. Schirmer Inc.|Schirmer Books]] |url= https://books.google.com/?id=r4qfAAAAMAAJ |edition= 1st |year= 1980 |page= 349}}</ref>|[[Southern rock]]<ref>{{cite magazine|author= Josh Jackson & Paste Music Staff |title= The 50 Best Southern Rock Albums of All Time |magazine= [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date= February 26, 2018 |accessdate= June 20, 2018 |url= https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/02/the-50-best-southern-rock-albums-of-all-time.html}}</ref>}}\n|years_active    = 1969\u2013present\n|label           = {{hlist|[[American Recordings (record label)|American]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]|[[London Records|London]]}}\n|associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Moving Sidewalks]]|[[American Blues]]}}\n|website         = {{url|zztop.com}}\n|current_members = \n* [[Billy Gibbons]]\n* [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]]\n* [[Dusty Hill]]\n|past_members    = \n* Lanier Greig\n* Dan Mitchell\n* Billy Ethridge}}\n\n'''ZZ Top''' (pronounced \"zee zee top\") is an American [[Rock music|rock]] band from [[Houston, Texas]], formed in 1969. The group consists of founder [[Billy Gibbons]] (guitar, lead vocals), [[Dusty Hill]] (bass, vocals) and [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]] (drums, percussion). Initially rooted in [[blues]], ZZ Top's style has evolved throughout their career, with a signature sound based on Gibbons' blues guitar style and Hill and Beard's rhythm section. Their lyrics, often embellished with [[sexual innuendo]], focus on their Texas roots and humor. Popular for their live performances, the group has staged several elaborate tours.\n \nZZ Top formed after the demise of Gibbons' previous band, [[Moving Sidewalks]]. Within a year, they signed with [[London Records]] and released ''[[ZZ Top's First Album]]'' (1971). Subsequent releases, such as their first top-ten album ''[[Tres Hombres]]'' (1973) and the singles \"[[La Grange (song)|La Grange]]\" and \"[[Tush (ZZ Top song)|Tush]]\", gained extensive radio airplay. By the mid-1970s, they had become renowned in North America for their live act, highlighted by their performances during the [[Worldwide Texas Tour]] from 1976 to 1977, which made them national stars and was a critical and commercial success.\n \nFollowing a two-year break after facing creative stagnation and exhaustion, ZZ Top reinvented themselves in the late 1970s with a new musical direction and public image. Beginning with their albums [[Deg\u00fcello]] (1979) and [[El Loco]] (1981), they experimented with instruments including [[clavinet]]s, [[saxophone]]s, and [[synthesizer]]s, while Gibbons and Hill grew long beards as part of their image. ZZ Top gained international favor with the records ''[[Eliminator (album)|Eliminator]]'' (1983) and ''[[Afterburner (ZZ Top album)|Afterburner]]'' (1985), which integrated influences from [[New wave music|new wave]], [[Punk rock|punk]], and [[dance-rock]], and established a more mainstream sound. The popularity of their [[Music video|music videos]], including those for \"[[Gimme All Your Lovin']]\", \"[[Sharp Dressed Man]]\", and \"[[Legs (song)|Legs]]\", helped propel them onto the television channel [[MTV]] and made them one of the more prominent artists in [[1980s#Popular_culture|1980s pop culture]]. Their [[Afterburner Tour]] set records for the highest-attended and highest-grossing concert tour of 1986. After additional acclaim with the release of their tenth album ''[[Recycler (album)|Recycler]]'' (1990) and the [[Recycler Tour]], their experimentation continued with the albums ''[[Antenna (ZZ Top album)|Antenna]]'' (1994), ''[[Rhythmeen]]'' (1996), ''[[XXX (ZZ Top album)|XXX]]'' (1999), and ''[[Mescalero (album)|Mescalero]]'' (2003), with mixed successes. The group most recently released ''[[La Futura]]'' (2012) and ''Goin\u2032 50'' (2019), the latter of which is a compilation album commemorating the band's 50th anniversary.\n\nZZ Top has released 15 studio albums and sold an estimated 50 million albums worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|first= Gabriel |last= Falcon |title= ZZ Top: After 50 years they've still got legs |publisher= [[CBS News]] |date= July 21, 2019 |accessdate= March 4, 2020 |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/zz-top-goin-50-dusty-hill-frank-beard-billy-gibbons/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Peter |last= Blackstock |title= ZZ Top at 50: Billy Gibbons takes us back to the beginning |newspaper= [[Austin American-Statesman]] |date= May 15, 2019 |accessdate= May 15, 2019 |url= https://www.austin360.com/entertainmentlife/20190515/zz-top-at-50-billy-gibbons-takes-us-back-to-beginning}}</ref> They have won three [[MTV Video Music Awards]], and in 2004, they were inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked Gibbons number 32 on its list of the \"100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\".<ref>{{cite magazine|title= 100 Greatest Guitarists |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |date= December 8, 2015 |accessdate= March 4, 2020 |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/100-greatest-guitarists-153675/billy-gibbons-153118/}}</ref> Throughout their career, as a band and as individuals, they have supported several campaigns and charities, including [[Childline]], [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]], and a fundraiser for the [[Delta Blues Museum]].\n\n==History==\n===Early years (1969\u20131972)===\nThe original line-up was formed in [[Houston]] and consisted of Gibbons, bassist/organist Lanier Greig,<ref name=\"HC\">{{cite news|first= Andrew |last= Dansby |title= Greig, early ZZ Top member, dies at 64 |newspaper= [[Houston Chronicle]] |date= February 16, 2013 |url= http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Lanier-Greig-musician-and-early-ZZ-Top-member-4284956.php |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> and drummer Dan Mitchell.<ref name=\"HC\"/>\n\nThe name of the band was Gibbons' idea. The band had a little apartment covered with concert posters and he noticed that many performers' names used initials. Gibbons particularly noticed [[B.B. King]] and [[Z. Z. Hill|Z.Z. Hill]] and thought of combining the two into \"ZZ King\", but considered it too similar to the original name. He then figured that \"king is going at the top\" which brought him to \"ZZ Top.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Uncle Joe Benson \u2013 The Story: ZZ Top 9-11-15 The Stor |publisher= [[SoundCloud]] |url= https://soundcloud.com/uncle-joe-benson/the-story-zz-top-9-11-15 |accessdate= September 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nZZ Top was managed by [[Bill Ham]], a [[Waxahachie, Texas]], native who had befriended Gibbons a year earlier. They released their first single, \"Salt Lick,\"  in 1969, and the B-side contained the song \"Miller's Farm.\" Both songs credited Gibbons as the composer. Immediately after the recording of \"Salt Lick,\" Greig was replaced by bassist Billy Ethridge, a bandmate of [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]], and Mitchell was replaced by [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]] of [[American Blues]]. Due to lack of interest from the major American record companies, ZZ Top accepted a record deal from [[London Records]], the American affiliate of the British [[Decca Records]] label. Unwilling to sign a recording contract, Ethridge quit the band and [[Dusty Hill]], Frank Beard's American Blues bandmate, became his replacement. After Hill moved from Dallas to Houston, ZZ Top signed with London in 1970. They performed their first concert together at the Knights of Columbus Hall in [[Beaumont, Texas]], on February 10, 1970.\n\nIn addition to assuming the role as the band's leader, Gibbons became the main lyricist and musical arranger. With the assistance of Ham and engineer Robin Hood Brians, ''[[ZZ Top's First Album]]'' (1971) was released and exhibited the band's humor, with \"barrelhouse\" rhythms, distorted guitars, double entendres, and innuendo. The music and songs reflected ZZ Top's blues influences. Following their debut album, the band released ''[[Rio Grande Mud]]'' (1972), which produced their first charting single.<ref>{{cite web|first= Matthew |last= Wilkening |title= Revisiting ZZ Top's Second Album, 'Rio Grande Mud' |website= [[Ultimate Classic Rock]] |date= April 4, 2015 |accessdate= June 5, 2019 |url= https://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-rio-grande-mud-turns-40/}}</ref>\n\n===First decade and signature sound (1973\u20131982)===\n[[File:ZZ Top (1976).png|230px|thumb|right|ZZ Top performing live in 1976]]\nZZ Top released ''[[Tres Hombres]]'' in 1973. The album's sound was the result of the propulsive support provided by Hill and Beard, and Gibbons' \"growling\" guitar tone. Dan Erlewine wrote that the album \"brought ZZ Top their first Top Ten record, making them stars in the process.\" The album included the boogie-driven \"[[La Grange (song)|La Grange]]\" (written about the [[Chicken Ranch (Texas)|Chicken Ranch]], a notorious brothel in [[La Grange, Texas]], that also inspired the musical ''[[The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas]]''). On the subsequent tour, the band performed sold-out concerts in the US. ZZ Top recorded the live tracks for their 1975 album, ''[[Fandango!]]'', during this tour. ''Fandango!'' was a top-ten album; its single \"[[Tush (ZZ Top song)|Tush]]\" peaked at number 20 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. ''[[Tejas (album)|Tejas]]'', released in 1976, was not as successful or as positively received as their previous efforts, although the album went to number 17 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Tejas \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/tejas-mw0000193395/awards |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> ZZ Top continued the [[Worldwide Texas Tour]] in support of ''Tejas'', though they had been touring for seven years.  The band then went on what was supposed to be a 90-day break from public appearances. Gibbons traveled to Europe, Beard went to [[Jamaica]], and Hill went to [[Mexico]].<ref>di Perna, Alan (July 2, 2008) {{cite web|url= http://www.guitarworld.com/article/zz_top_cars_guitars_three_unlikely_rock_stars?page=0,8 |title= ZZ Top: Cars, Guitars, & Three Unlikely Rock Stars |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081030192921/http://www.guitarworld.com/article/zz_top_cars_guitars_three_unlikely_rock_stars?page=0,8 |archivedate= October 30, 2008}}. ''[[Guitar World]]''.</ref> The break extended to two years, during which Gibbons and Hill grew chest-length [[beard]]s.<ref>Tom Vickers, sleeve notes for ''[[Rancho Texicano]]'' (Warner Bros Records Inc., 2004).</ref>\n\nIn 1979, ZZ Top signed with [[Warner Bros. Records]] and released the album ''[[Deg\u00fcello]]''. While the album went platinum, it only reached number 24 on the ''Billboard'' chart.<ref>{{cite web|title= Deg\u00fcello \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |accessdate= July 28, 2014 |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/deg%C3%BCello-mw0000651021/awards}}</ref> The album produced two popular singles: \"[[I Thank You (song)|I Thank You]]\", a cover of a song recorded by [[Sam & Dave]], and \"[[Cheap Sunglasses]]\". The band remained a popular concert attraction and [[Expect No Quarter Tour|toured in support of ''Deg\u00fcello'']]. In April 1980, ZZ Top made their first appearance in Europe, performing for the German music television show ''[[Rockpalast]]''. Their next album, ''[[El Loco]]'', was released in October 1981, and featured the singles \"[[Tube Snake Boogie]]\", \"[[Pearl Necklace (song)|Pearl Necklace]]\", and \"Leila\".<ref>{{cite web|title= El Loco \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |accessdate= July 28, 2014 |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/el-loco-mw0000197282/awards}}</ref>\n\n===''Eliminator'', ''Afterburner'', and ''Recycler'' (1983\u20131991)===\n[[File:ZZTop.jpg|thumb|230px|right|Hill and Gibbons in 1983]]\nZZ Top's next album was even more successful. ''[[Eliminator (album)|Eliminator]]'', released in March 1983, featured two top-40 singles (\"[[Gimme All Your Lovin']]\" and \"[[Legs (song)|Legs]]\"), and two additional [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Top Rock]] hits (\"[[Got Me Under Pressure]]\" and \"[[Sharp Dressed Man]]\"), with \"Legs\" peaking at number 13 on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Club Play Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title= Eliminator \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/eliminator-mw0000192586/awards |accessdate= July 28, 2013}}</ref> ''Eliminator'' was a critical and commercial success, selling more than 10 million copies,<ref name=\"riaa2\">{{cite web|title= RIAA \u2013 Gold & Platinum Searchable Database \u2013 Eliminator |publisher= [[Recording Industry Association of America]] |url= https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=eliminator#search_section |accessdate= November 19, 2016}}</ref> and several music videos were in regular rotation on MTV. The band also won their first [[MTV Video Music Award]]s in the categories of [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Group Video|Best Group Video]] for \"Legs\", and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]] for \"Sharp Dressed Man\". The music videos were included in their ''[[Greatest Hits (ZZ Top DVD)|Greatest Hits]]'' video, which was later released on DVD and quickly went multiple-platinum.<ref name=\"riaa2\"/> However, the ''Eliminator'' album was not without controversy. According to former stage manager David Blayney in his book \"''Sharp Dressed Men\"'', sound engineer Linden Hudson co-wrote much of the material on the album while serving as a live-in high-tech music teacher to Beard and Gibbons. Despite continued denials by the band, it settled a five-year legal battle with Hudson, paying him $600,000 after he proved he held the copyright to the song \"Thug\".<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Blayney |title= Sharp Dressed Men |location= New York |publisher= [[Hachette Books|Hyperion]] |year= 1994 |isbn= 0-7868-8005-8 |pages= 196\u2013203}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= Deborah |last= Frost |title= ZZ Top - Bad And Worldwide |location= New York |publisher= Rolling Stone Press |year= 1985 |isbn= 0020029500}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Sinclair |title= Tres Hombres: The Story of ZZ Top |publisher= [[Virgin Books|Virgin]] |year= 1986 |isbn= 0-86369-167-6}}</ref>\n\nDespite not selling as many copies as ''Eliminator'', 1985's ''[[Afterburner (ZZ Top album)|Afterburner]]'' became the band's highest-charting album,<ref name=\"Afterburner\">{{cite web|title= Afterburner \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |accessdate= July 28, 2013 |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/afterburner-mw0000196478/awards}}</ref> racking up sales of five million units.<ref name=\"riaa2\"/> All of the singles from ''Afterburner'' were Top-40 hits, with two (\"Sleeping Bag\" and \"Stages\") hitting number one on the Mainstream Rock chart.<ref name=\"Afterburner\"/> The music video for \"[[Velcro Fly]]\" was choreographed by pop singer [[Paula Abdul]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Paula Abdul \u2013 Times Topics |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= August 5, 2009 |url= http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/a/paula_abdul/index.html |accessdate= December 19, 2010}}</ref> ZZ Top's grueling [[Afterburner World Tour]] lasted well into 1987, which also had the release of ''The ZZ Top Sixpack'', a three-disc collection of ZZ Top's albums from 1970 to 1981, with the exception of ''Deg\u00fcello''. The albums ''ZZ Top's First Album'', ''Rio Grande Mud'', ''Tres Hombres'', ''Fandango'', and ''Tejas'' were remixed to have a more contemporary sound.<ref>{{cite book|first= Bob |last= Merlis |first2= Jim |last2= Bessman |title= ZZ on CD: Meeting The Digital Challenge Head On |location= ZZ Top Six Pack CD Booklet |publisher= Warner Bros Records |year= 1987 |page= 2}}</ref>\n\n''[[Recycler (ZZ Top album)|Recycler]]'', released in 1990, was ZZ Top's last studio album under contract with Warner Records. ''Recycler'' was also the last of a distinct sonic trilogy in the ZZ Top catalogue, marking a return towards a simpler guitar-driven blues sound with less synthesizer and pop bounce than the previous two albums. This move did not entirely suit the fan base that ''Eliminator'' and ''Afterburner'' had built up, and while ''Recycler'' did achieve platinum status, it never matched the sales of those albums. However, the single \"[[My Head's in Mississippi]]\" did reach No. 1 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Album Rock Tracks]] chart that year.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mainstream Rock: Dec 08, 1990 |work= Billboard |accessdate= July 21, 2019 |url= http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/1990-12-08/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks}}</ref>\n\n===Return to guitar-driven sound (1992\u20132003)===\nIn 1992, Warner released ''ZZ Top's Greatest Hits'', along with a new [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]]-style cut, \"Gun Love\", and an [[Elvis Presley|Elvis]]-inflected video, \"[[Viva Las Vegas (song)|Viva Las Vegas]]\". In 1993, ZZ Top inducted a major influence, [[Cream (band)|Cream]], into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].\n\nIn 1994, the band signed a $35 million deal with [[RCA Records]],<ref name=\"rockhonors\">{{cite web|title= VH1 Rock Honors 2007 \u2013 Honorees |year= 2007 |publisher= [[VH1]] |url= http://www.vh1.com/shows/events/rock_honors/_2007/honorees.jhtml |accessdate= December 19, 2010}}</ref> releasing the million-selling ''[[Antenna (ZZ Top album)|Antenna.]]'' Subsequent RCA albums, ''[[Rhythmeen]]'' (1996) and 1999's ''[[XXX (ZZ Top album)|XXX]]'' (the second album to feature live tracks) sold well, but did not reach the levels enjoyed previously. In 2003, ZZ Top released a final RCA album, ''[[Mescalero (album)|Mescalero]]'', an album thick with harsh Gibbons guitar and featuring a [[hidden track]]\u2014a cover version of \"[[As Time Goes By (song)|As Time Goes By.]]\" RCA impresario Clive Davis wanted to do a collaboration record (in the mode of [[Carlos Santana]]'s successful ''Supernatural'') for this album. In an interview in ''[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]]'' magazine, Davis stated that artists [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Dave Matthews]], and [[Wilco]] were among the artists slated for the project. ZZ Top performed \"Tush\" and \"Legs\" as part of the [[Super Bowl XXXI]] halftime show in 1997.\n\nA comprehensive four-CD collection of recordings from the London and Warner Bros. years, ''[[Chrome, Smoke & BBQ]]'', was released in 2003. It featured the band's first single (A- and B-side) and several rare B-side tracks, as well as a radio promotion from 1979, a live track, and several extended dance-mix versions of their biggest MTV hits. Three tracks from Billy Gibbons' pre-ZZ band, the [[Moving Sidewalks]], were also included.\n\n===Critical acclaim and retrospective releases (2004\u20132011)===\nIn 2004, ZZ Top was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]. [[Keith Richards]] of [[the Rolling Stones]] gave the induction speech. ZZ Top gave a brief performance, playing \"La Grange\" and \"Tush\".\n\n[[File:ZZ Top, 26Jun2010.jpg|thumb|left|ZZ Top at the [[Crossroads Guitar Festival]], on June 26, 2010]]\n\nExpanded and remastered versions of the original studio albums from the 1970s and 1980s are currently{{when|date=May 2018}} in production. Marketed as \"Remastered and Expanded\", these releases include additional live tracks which were not present on the original recordings. Three such CDs have been released to date (''Tres Hombres'', ''Fandango!'', and ''Eliminator''). The first two were released in 2006 and use the original mixes free from echo and drum machines, while ''Eliminator'' was released in 2008. The ''Eliminator'' re-release also features a collector's edition version containing a DVD featuring several videos and additional live tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.zztop.com/index.php?module=news_item&news_item_id=116 |title= \"Eliminator\" Reissue Coming March 25th! |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110718161726/http://www.zztop.com/index.php?module=news_item&news_item_id=116 |archivedate= July 18, 2011}}. ZZtop.com. January 14, 2008.</ref>\n\nThe ''Eliminator Collector's Edition'' CD/DVD, celebrating the 25th anniversary of the band's iconic RIAA Diamond Certified album, was released September 10, 2008. The release includes seven bonus tracks and a bonus DVD, including four television performances from ''[[The Tube (TV series)|The Tube]]'' in November 1983.\n\nThe band performed at the 2009 [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] on the final night on March 22, 2009. In July, the band appeared on [[VH1]]'s ''[[VH1 Storytellers|Storytellers]]'', in celebration of their four decades as recording artists.<ref>{{cite press release|title= VH1 To Premiere ZZ Top \"Storytellers\" |url= http://www.icelebz.com/gossips/tv/vh1_to_premiere_zz_top_storytellers_/ |agency= [[All Headline News|AHN]] |date= June 10, 2009 |accessdate= December 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===''La Futura'' and possible sixteenth studio album (2012\u2013present)===\n[[File:ZZ.TOP_2_rkent_at_mac_dot_com.jpg|thumb|ZZ Top at the Alamodome in San Antonio, Texas, November 7, 2013]]\n[[File:ZZ Top 2015.jpg|thumb|ZZ Top performing at the [[Majestic Theatre (San Antonio)|Majestic Theatre]] in San Antonio in 2015]]\nBilly Gibbons stated in an interview in August 2011 that a new album had been recorded, with initial recording taking place in [[Malibu, California]], before moving to Houston, but was still unnamed and had yet to be mixed and mastered.<ref name=\"ucr\"/> Gibbons said that the expected release date was sometime in March or April 2012, but later on a release in the late summer or early fall was announced.<ref name=\"ucr\">{{cite web|title= ZZ Top 'Sowing and Stitching Away' at New Album, Says Billy Gibbons |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-new-album-march-2012/ |accessdate= September 22, 2011 |archivedate= December 25, 2011 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111225070034/http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-new-album-march-2012/}}</ref> The album was subsequently released on  September 11, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://zztop.com/news/90461 |title= La Futura Arrives This September From ZZ Top |website= ZZtop.com |date= August 3, 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121014013711/http://zztop.com/news/90461 |archivedate= October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nEntitled ''[[La Futura]]'', the album was produced by [[Rick Rubin]].<ref>{{cite magazine|first= David |last= Fricke |first2= Eric |last2= Helton |first3= Matthew |last3= Murphy |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/zz-top-billy-gibbons-on-the-bands-next-album-20111129 |title= Billy Gibbons on the band's next album |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |date= November 29, 2011 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= La Futura By ZZ Top |publisher= MP396 |url= http://mp396.com/la-futura-by-zz-top.html  |date= September 13, 2012 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> The first single from the album, \"I Gotsta Get Paid\", debuted in an advertising campaign for [[Jeremiah Weed|Jeremiah Weed Whiskey]] and appears on the soundtrack of the film ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title= Battleship (2012) \u2013 Soundtracks |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1440129/soundtrack |publisher= [[Internet Movie Database]] |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> The song itself is an interpretation of \"25 Lighters\" by Texan hip hop DJ DMD and rappers [[Lil' Keke]] and [[Fat Pat (rapper)|Fat Pat]].<ref>{{cite web|first= Jeff |last= Giles |title= ZZ Top's New Single Based on '90s Rap Song |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-new-single-based-on-90s-rap-song/ |date= May 30, 2012 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> The first four songs from ''La Futura'' debuted on June 5, 2012, on an EP called ''Texicali''.<ref>{{cite web|title= Release Day! |url= http://www.zztop.com/news/81091%20Texicali |website= ZZtop.com |accessdate= July 7, 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140729014435/http://www.zztop.com/news/81091%20Texicali |archivedate= July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[DJ Screw]] was a major influence on the album as well, particularly because Gibbons and Screw both worked with engineer G. L. Moon during the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|first= Ben |last= Ratliff |title= Traveling at the Speed of Molasses |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/09/arts/music/for-zz-top-new-album-la-futura-and-a-tour.html?_r=2& |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= September 6, 2012 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ZZ top Steifel theatre 2016.jpg|ZZ Top in September 2016|thumb]]\nThe band kicked off a North American tour with a concert in Red Bank, New Jersey, at the Count Basie Theatre on March 3, 2015. After rescheduled dates and additions, the tour wrapped up with a concert in Highland Park, Illinois, at the Ravinia Pavilion on August 27, with opening act [[Blackberry Smoke]]. [[Jeff Beck]] joined ZZ Top for seven concerts on the tour.<ref>{{cite web|title= ZZ Top 2015 North American Tour Schedule With Jeff Beck & Blackberry Smoke |website= Zz-top.concerttournewshub |url= http://ZZ-Top.concerttournewshub.com/ |accessdate= March 29, 2015 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151006085950/http://zz-top.concerttournewshub.com/ |archivedate= October 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Upcoming Tour Dates |publisher= Zztop.com |url= http://www.zztop.com/tour/ |accessdate= March 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2016, ZZ Top released a new live album entitled ''Tonite at Midnight: Live Greatest Hits from Around the World''.\n\nIn 2017, ZZ Top announced their \"[[Tonnage Tour|2017 Tonnage Tour]]\" which was to last from February 19 to March 14.<ref>{{cite web|first= Jeff |last= Giles |title= ZZ Top Announce 2017 'Tonnage' Tour |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= October 25, 2016 |accessdate= October 1, 2018 |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-2017-tour/}}</ref> However, they were forced to cancel last few dates of their tour due to the ailment of bassist Dusty Hill.<ref>{{cite web|first= Matthew |last= Wilkening |title= ZZ Top Cancel Remaining 2017 Tour Dates |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= October 17, 2017 |accessdate= October 1, 2018 |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-cancel-2017-tour/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the band announced their six-day Las Vegas run of shows to be held at [[The Venetian Las Vegas|The Venetian]], starting from April 20, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title= ZZ Top returning to Venetian in 2019 |publisher= [[KTNV-TV]] |date= September 24, 2018 |accessdate= October 1, 2018 |url= https://www.ktnv.com/positivelylv/zz-top-returning-to-venetian-in-2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a September 2019 interview with ''[[Ultimate Classic Rock]]'', Hill stated that \"there's a good chance\" ZZ Top will release a follow-up to ''La Futura'': \"We've got a lot in the can. It depends on how we would want to put it together or redo it or whatever. Because it's years of stuff. We just record everything, and then we go, 'Well, no, this didn't quite feel right, right now.'\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Dave |last= Lifton |title= Dusty Hill Says There's a 'Good Chance' of Another ZZ Top Album |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= September 3, 2019 |accessdate= December 22, 2019 |url= https://ultimateclassicrock.com/dusty-hill-new-zz-top-album/}}</ref>\n\n==Other appearances==\nZZ Top performed at the 2008 [[Orange Bowl]] game in [[Miami]], as well as the [[Auto Club 400|Auto Club 500]] [[NASCAR]] event at the [[Auto Club Speedway]] in [[Fontana, California]]. On June 23, 2008, ZZ Top celebrated the release of their first live concert DVD titled ''[[Live from Texas]]'' with the world premiere, a special appearance, and charity auction at the [[Hard Rock Cafe]] in Houston.<ref>{{cite web|title= EVENTS |url= http://www.hardrock.com/Locations/Cafes3/events.aspx?LocationID=56&MIBenumID=3&EventID=31464 |date= June 23, 2008 |website= Hardrock.com |accessdate= October 2, 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110928224155/http://www.hardrock.com/Locations/Cafes3/events.aspx?LocationID=56&MIBenumID=3&EventID=31464 |archivedate= September 28, 2011}}</ref> The DVD was officially released on June 24, 2008. The featured performance was culled from a concert filmed at the Nokia Theater in Grand Prairie, Texas, on November 1, 2007.\n\nOn January 22, 2010, Billy Gibbons accompanied [[Will Ferrell]] and others playing \"[[Free Bird]]\" on [[Conan O'Brien]]'s last ''Tonight Show'' appearance. O'Brien joined in on guitar.<ref>{{cite press release|first= Natalie |last= Rotman |title= O'Brien ends run on 'Tonight' show after 7 months |agency= [[Associated Press]] |date= January 23, 2010 |url= http://newsok.com/obrien-ends-run-on-tonight-show-after-7-months/article/feed/126519 |accessdate= May 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, various media sources reported that the new song \"Flyin' High\" would debut in space. Astronaut and friend of ZZ Top, [[Michael E. Fossum|Michael Fossum]], was given the released single to listen to on his trip to the International Space Station.<ref>{{cite web|title= ZZ Top Debuts New Song In Space |url= http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/zz_top_debuts_new_song_in_space.html |publisher= Ultimate-guitar.com |date= August 6, 2001 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= Spencer |last= Kaufman |title= ZZ Top Premiere New Song 'Flyin' High' on Russian Spacecraft |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= June 9, 2011 |accessdate= September 30, 2019 |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-flyin-high-russian-spacecraft/}}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2014, ZZ Top opened the CMT Awards performing \"La Grange\" with [[Luke Bryan]] and [[Florida Georgia Line]].\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Billy Gibbons]] \u2013 guitar, lead and backing vocals, harmonica (1969\u2013present)\n* [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]] \u2013 drums, percussion, backing vocals (1969\u2013present)\n* [[Dusty Hill]] \u2013 bass, backing and lead vocals, keyboards (1969\u2013present)\n\n'''Touring substitutes'''\n* John Douglas \u2013 drums, percussion (2002)\n\n'''Session guests'''\n* Pete Tickle \u2013 acoustic guitar on \"Mushmouth Shoutin'\" from ''[[Rio Grande Mud]]'' (1971)\n* [[Terry Manning]] \u2013 synthesizer, drum machine on ''[[Eliminator (album)|Eliminator]]'' (1982)\n* [[James Harman]] \u2013 harmonica on \"[[What's Up with That (ZZ Top song)|What's Up with That]]\" from ''[[Rhythmeen]]'' (1996); ''[[Mescalero (album)|Mescalero]]'' (2002); ''[[La Futura]]'' (2012)\n* Marimbas de Chiapas \u2013 marimba on ''Mescalero'' (2002)\n* [[Dan Dugmore]] \u2013 pedal steel guitar on ''Mescalero'' (2002)\n* Joe Hardy \u2013 piano, Hammond B3 organ on ''La Futura'' (2012)\n* Dave Sardy \u2013 piano, Hammond B3 organ on ''La Futura'' (2012)\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Lanier Greig \u2013 bass, Hammond organ (1969)<ref>{{cite web|first= Jeff |last= Giles |title= Meet the OTHER Three Members of ZZ Top |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= February 21, 2014 |accessdate= September 16, 2017 |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-other-members/}}</ref>\n* Dan Mitchell \u2013 drums (1969)\n* Billy Ethridge \u2013 bass (1969)\n\n'''Touring guests'''\n* [[Jeff Beck]] \u2013 guitar on \"Hey Mr. Millionaire\" from ''[[XXX (ZZ Top album)|XXX]]'' (1999)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|ZZ Top discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n{{div col}}\n* ''[[ZZ Top's First Album]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[Rio Grande Mud]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Tres Hombres]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Fandango!]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Tejas (album)|Tejas]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Deg\u00fcello]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[El Loco]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Eliminator (album)|Eliminator]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Afterburner (ZZ Top album)|Afterburner]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Recycler (album)|Recycler]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Antenna (ZZ Top album)|Antenna]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Rhythmeen]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[XXX (ZZ Top album)|XXX]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Mescalero (album)|Mescalero]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[La Futura]]'' (2012)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Filmography==\nIn addition to recording and performing concerts, ZZ Top has also been involved with films and television. In 1990, the group appeared as the \"band at the party\" in the film ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]''<ref>{{cite web|title= Back to the Future Part III (1990) \u2013 Full Cast & Crew |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0099088/fullcredits#cast |publisher= Internet Movie Database |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> and played the \"Three Men in a Tub\" in the movie ''[[Mother Goose Rock 'n' Rhyme]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mother Goose Rock 'n' Rhyme (1990) \u2013 Full Cast & Crew |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0100192/fullcredits#cast |publisher= Internet Movie Database |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> ZZ Top made further appearances, including the \"Gumby with a Pokey\" episode of ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'' in 2010<ref>{{cite web|title= \"Two and a Half Men\" Gumby with a Pokey (2010) \u2013 Full Cast & Crew |publisher= Internet Movie Database |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1646007/fullcredits#cast |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> and the \"[[Hank Gets Dusted]]\" episode of ''[[King of the Hill]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title= \"King of the Hill\" Hank Gets Dusted (TV episode 2007) |publisher= Internet Movie Database |year= 2007 |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0995437/ |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> The band also [[List of WWE Raw guest stars|guest hosted]] an episode of [[WWE Raw]].<ref>{{cite web|title= WWF Raw Is War \u2013 Episode dated 20 July 2009 |publisher= Internet Movie Database |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0995437/ |year= 2009 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> Billy Gibbons also had a recurring role as the father of [[Angela Montenegro]] in the television show ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''; though the character is never named, it is strongly implied that Gibbons is playing himself.<ref>{{cite web|first= Sean |last= Axmaster |title= The Love Story of Bones' Booth and Brennan in 12 Episodes |website= [[Vulture.com]] |date= March 28, 2017 |accessdate= April 22, 2017 |url= http://www.vulture.com/2017/03/bones-booth-brennan-love-story-primer.html}}</ref> Their song \"Sharp Dressed Man\" was one of the theme songs used for the television show ''[[Duck Dynasty]]'', and on the series finale of the show they appeared with [[Si Robertson]] as a vocalist to perform the song on stage during Robertson's retirement party.<ref>{{cite web|title= Legendary Rock Band Makes Surprise Appearance on Final Episode of 'Duck Dynasty' |website= Country Rebel |accessdate= April 22, 2017 |url= https://countryrebel.com/blogs/videos/legendary-rock-group-makes-surprise-appearance-on-final-episode-of-duck-dynasty}}</ref> Black Dahlia Films, led by Jamie Burton Chamberlin, of [[Seattle]] and [[Los Angeles]], has contributed documentaries and [[Live event support|back line screen]] work (the footage on back screens during live shows) and has become an integral part of the band's film-making.<ref>{{cite web|title= Black Dahlia Films + Seattle, WA |url= http://www.blackdahliafilms.com/releases.html |publisher= Blackdahliafilms.com |accessdate= February 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= New ZZ Top tour features West Seattle talent |newspaper= [[West Seattle Herald]] |url= http://www.westseattleherald.com/2012/07/09/features/new-zz-top-tour-features-west-seattle-talent |date= September 7, 2012 |accessdate= February 22, 2015}}</ref> ZZ Top made a guest appearance in the episode \"Sweet Dreams\" (Season 3 Episode 8) of the television show ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'' on November 14, 1984. While the band appears in Luther's dream, once Luther wakes he finds the \"Z\" keychain in the lock of the door to the room he was sleeping in.\n\n==Awards and achievements==\nZZ Top's music videos won multiple [[MTV Video Music Award|VMA]] awards during the 1980s, topping the categories of [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Group Video|Best Group Video]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]], and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]] for \"Legs\", \"Sharp Dressed Man\" and \"[[Rough Boy]]\", respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title= 1986 Video Music Awards |publisher= MTV. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] |url= http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1986/ |accessdate= December 19, 2010}}</ref> Among high honors for ZZ Top have been induction into [[Guitar Center#Hollywood's RockWalk|Hollywood's RockWalk]] in 1994,<ref>{{cite web|title= Hollywood's RockWalk \u2013 ZZ Top |url= http://www.rockwalk.com/inductees/inductee.cfm?id=150 |publisher= [[Guitar Center]] |year= 2007 |accessdate= December 19, 2010}}</ref> the [[Texas House of Representatives]] naming them \"Official Heroes for the State of Texas\",<ref>{{cite news|first= David |last= Yonke |title= ZZ Top: Rocking hard since '69 |newspaper= [[The Blade (Toledo, Ohio)|Toledo Blade]] |date= September 9, 2009 |url= http://www.deltabluesmuseum.org/high/press_090907.asp |accessdate= December 18, 2010}}</ref> a declaration of \"ZZ Top Day\" in Texas by then-governor [[Ann Richards]] on May 4, 1991,<ref>{{cite press release|title= Member News Releases |publisher= [[Texas House of Representatives]] |date= September 29, 2005 |accessdate= December 18, 2010 |url= http://www.house.state.tx.us/news/press-releases/print/?id=1468}}</ref> and induction into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 2004. They were also given commemorative rings by actor [[Billy Bob Thornton]] from the [[VH1 Rock Honors]] in 2007.<ref name=\"rockhonors\"/>\n\nZZ Top has also achieved several chart and album sales feats, including six number-one singles on the [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock chart]]. From the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]], ZZ Top has earned four gold, three platinum and two multiple-platinum album certifications, and one diamond album.<ref name=\"riaa2\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|ZZ Top}}\n*[[ZZ Top equipment]]\n*[[List of artists who reached number one on the U.S. Mainstream Rock chart]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|first=David|last=Thomas|author-link=Dave Thompson (author)|title=Elimination \u2013 The ZZ Top Story|year=1985|location=London|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|isbn=0711907188}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q136591|c=Category:ZZ Top|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no|q=no}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{Curlie|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/Z/ZZ_Top/}}\n*{{Rockhall}}\n\n{{ZZ Top|state=expanded}}\n{{2004 Rock and Roll Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zz Top}}\n[[Category:ZZ Top| ]]\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:American blues rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Hard rock musical groups from Texas]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Houston]]\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Southern rock musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rock band}}\n{{use mdy dates |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = ZZ Top\n|image           = ZZ Top on the Pyramid Stage at Glastonbury 2016 IMG 8527 (27374417884).jpg\n|image_size      = 350\n|caption         = ZZ Top (from left: [[Dusty Hill]], [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]], [[Billy Gibbons]]) at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] in June 2016\n|landscape       = yes\n|background      = group_or_band\n|origin          = [[Houston]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n|genre           = {{hlist|[[Blues rock]]<ref>{{cite web|first= Cub |last= Koda |title= ZZ Top \u2013 Artist Biography |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/zz-top-mn0000690254/biography |publisher= [[AllMusic]]. [[All Media Network]] |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-first= Patricia |editor-last= Bashe |editor-first2= Holly |editor-last2= George-Warren |year= 2001 |title= The Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll |url= https://archive.org/details/rollingstoneency00holl |edition= 3rd |publisher= [[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn= 978-0-7432-0120-9 |url-access= registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= Nick |last= Talevski |title= Rock Obituaries \u2013 Knocking On Heaven's Door |publisher= [[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]] |year= 2006 |page= 173 |isbn= 978-1-8460-9091-2}}</ref>|[[boogie rock]]<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Fred |last= Bonson |title= Wea's Greatest Hits |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume= 108 |issue= 35 |date= August 31, 1996 |page= 34 |quote= It was the band's second album, \"Tres Hombres,\" that established their boogie-rock credentials by peaking at No. 8 in 1974. |issn= 0006-2510}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= Matt |last= Cibula |url= http://www.popmatters.com/review/zztop-mescalero/ |title= ZZ Top: Mescalero |work= [[PopMatters]] |date= January 4, 2004 |accessdate= February 20, 2014}}</ref>|[[hard rock]]<ref>{{cite book|title= If You Like Metallica... |first= Mike |last= McPadden |year= 2012 |publisher= [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Backbeat Books]] |chapter= ZZ Top |chapter-url= https://books.google.com/?id=9o978TWC1hAC&pg=PT30 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= Ronald |last= Zalkind |title= Contemporary Music Almanac: 1980\u20131981 |publisher= [[G. Schirmer Inc.|Schirmer Books]] |url= https://books.google.com/?id=r4qfAAAAMAAJ |edition= 1st |year= 1980 |page= 349}}</ref>|[[Southern rock]]<ref>{{cite magazine|author= Josh Jackson & Paste Music Staff |title= The 50 Best Southern Rock Albums of All Time |magazine= [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date= February 26, 2018 |accessdate= June 20, 2018 |url= https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/02/the-50-best-southern-rock-albums-of-all-time.html}}</ref>}}\n|years_active    = 1969\u2013present\n|label           = {{hlist|[[American Recordings (record label)|American]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]|[[London Records|London]]}}\n|associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Moving Sidewalks]]|[[American Blues]]}}\n|website         = {{url|zztop.com}}\n|current_members = \n* [[Billy Gibbons]]\n* [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]]\n* [[Dusty Hill]]\n|past_members    = \n* Lanier Greig\n* Dan Mitchell\n* Billy Ethridge}}\n\n'''ZZ Top''' (pronounced \"zee zee top\") is an American [[Rock music|rock]] band from [[Houston, Texas]], formed in 1969. The group consists of founder [[Billy Gibbons]] (guitar, lead vocals), [[Dusty Hill]] (bass, vocals) and [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]] (drums, percussion). Initially rooted in [[blues]], ZZ Top's style has evolved throughout their career, with a signature sound based on Gibbons' blues guitar style and Hill and Beard's rhythm section. Their lyrics, often embellished with [[sexual innuendo]], focus on their Texas roots and humor. Popular for their live performances, the group has staged several elaborate tours.\n \nZZ Top formed after the demise of Gibbons' previous band, [[Moving Sidewalks]]. Within a year, they signed with [[London Records]] and released ''[[ZZ Top's First Album]]'' (1971). Subsequent releases, such as their first top-ten album ''[[Tres Hombres]]'' (1973) and the singles \"[[La Grange (song)|La Grange]]\" and \"[[Tush (ZZ Top song)|Tush]]\", gained extensive radio airplay. By the mid-1970s, they had become renowned in North America for their live act, highlighted by their performances during the [[Worldwide Texas Tour]] from 1976 to 1977, which made them national stars and was a critical and commercial success.\n \nFollowing a two-year break after facing creative stagnation and exhaustion, ZZ Top reinvented themselves in the late 1970s with a new musical direction and public image. Beginning with their albums [[Deg\u00fcello]] (1979) and [[El Loco]] (1981), they experimented with instruments including [[clavinet]]s, [[saxophone]]s, and [[synthesizer]]s, while Gibbons and Hill grew long beards as part of their image. ZZ Top gained international favor with the records ''[[Eliminator (album)|Eliminator]]'' (1983) and ''[[Afterburner (ZZ Top album)|Afterburner]]'' (1985), which integrated influences from [[New wave music|new wave]], [[Punk rock|punk]], and [[dance-rock]], and established a more mainstream sound. The popularity of their [[Music video|music videos]], including those for \"[[Gimme All Your Lovin']]\", \"[[Sharp Dressed Man]]\", and \"[[Legs (song)|Legs]]\", helped propel them onto the television channel [[MTV]] and made them one of the more prominent artists in [[1980s#Popular_culture|1980s pop culture]]. Their [[Afterburner Tour]] set records for the highest-attended and highest-grossing concert tour of 1986. After additional acclaim with the release of their tenth album ''[[Recycler (album)|Recycler]]'' (1990) and the [[Recycler Tour]], their experimentation continued with the albums ''[[Antenna (ZZ Top album)|Antenna]]'' (1994), ''[[Rhythmeen]]'' (1996), ''[[XXX (ZZ Top album)|XXX]]'' (1999), and ''[[Mescalero (album)|Mescalero]]'' (2003), with mixed successes. The group most recently released ''[[La Futura]]'' (2012) and ''Goin\u2032 50'' (2019), the latter of which is a compilation album commemorating the band's 50th anniversary.\n\nZZ Top has released 15 studio albums and sold an estimated 50 million albums worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|first= Gabriel |last= Falcon |title= ZZ Top: After 50 years they've still got legs |publisher= [[CBS News]] |date= July 21, 2019 |accessdate= March 4, 2020 |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/zz-top-goin-50-dusty-hill-frank-beard-billy-gibbons/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Peter |last= Blackstock |title= ZZ Top at 50: Billy Gibbons takes us back to the beginning |newspaper= [[Austin American-Statesman]] |date= May 15, 2019 |accessdate= May 15, 2019 |url= https://www.austin360.com/entertainmentlife/20190515/zz-top-at-50-billy-gibbons-takes-us-back-to-beginning}}</ref> They have won three [[MTV Video Music Awards]], and in 2004, they were inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked Gibbons number 32 on its list of the \"100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\".<ref>{{cite magazine|title= 100 Greatest Guitarists |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |date= December 8, 2015 |accessdate= March 4, 2020 |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/100-greatest-guitarists-153675/billy-gibbons-153118/}}</ref> Throughout their career, as a band and as individuals, they have supported several campaigns and charities, including [[Childline]], [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]], and a fundraiser for the [[Delta Blues Museum]].\n\n==History==\n===Early years (1969\u20131972)===\nThe original line-up was formed in [[Houston]] and consisted of Gibbons, bassist/organist Lanier Greig,<ref name=\"HC\">{{cite news|first= Andrew |last= Dansby |title= Greig, early ZZ Top member, dies at 64 |newspaper= [[Houston Chronicle]] |date= February 16, 2013 |url= http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Lanier-Greig-musician-and-early-ZZ-Top-member-4284956.php |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> and drummer Dan Mitchell.<ref name=\"HC\"/>\n\nThe name of the band was Gibbons' idea. The band had a little apartment covered with concert posters and he noticed that many performers' names used initials. Gibbons particularly noticed [[B.B. King]] and [[Z. Z. Hill|Z.Z. Hill]] and thought of combining the two into \"ZZ King\", but considered it too similar to the original name. He then figured that \"king is going at the top\" which brought him to \"ZZ Top.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Uncle Joe Benson \u2013 The Story: ZZ Top 9-11-15 The Stor |publisher= [[SoundCloud]] |url= https://soundcloud.com/uncle-joe-benson/the-story-zz-top-9-11-15 |accessdate= September 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nZZ Top was managed by [[Bill Ham]], a [[Waxahachie, Texas]], native who had befriended Gibbons a year earlier. They released their first single, \"Salt Lick,\"  in 1969, and the B-side contained the song \"Miller's Farm.\" Both songs credited Gibbons as the composer. Immediately after the recording of \"Salt Lick,\" Greig was replaced by bassist Billy Ethridge, a bandmate of [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]], and Mitchell was replaced by [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]] of [[American Blues]]. Due to lack of interest from the major American record companies, ZZ Top accepted a record deal from [[London Records]], the American affiliate of the British [[Decca Records]] label. Unwilling to sign a recording contract, Ethridge quit the band and [[Dusty Hill]], who had played with Frank Beard in American Blues, became his replacement. After Hill moved from Dallas to Houston, ZZ Top signed with London in 1970. They performed their first concert together at the Knights of Columbus Hall in [[Beaumont, Texas]], on February 10, 1970.\n\nIn addition to assuming the role as the band's leader, Gibbons became the main lyricist and musical arranger. With the assistance of Ham and engineer Robin Hood Brians, ''[[ZZ Top's First Album]]'' (1971) was released and exhibited the band's humor, with \"barrelhouse\" rhythms, distorted guitars, double entendres, and innuendo. The music and songs reflected ZZ Top's blues influences. Following their debut album, the band released ''[[Rio Grande Mud]]'' (1972), which produced their first charting single.<ref>{{cite web|first= Matthew |last= Wilkening |title= Revisiting ZZ Top's Second Album, 'Rio Grande Mud' |website= [[Ultimate Classic Rock]] |date= April 4, 2015 |accessdate= June 5, 2019 |url= https://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-rio-grande-mud-turns-40/}}</ref>\n\n===First decade and signature sound (1973\u20131982)===\n[[File:ZZ Top (1976).png|230px|thumb|right|ZZ Top performing live in 1976]]\nZZ Top released ''[[Tres Hombres]]'' in 1973. The album's sound was the result of the propulsive support provided by Hill and Beard, and Gibbons' \"growling\" guitar tone. Dan Erlewine wrote that the album \"brought ZZ Top their first Top Ten record, making them stars in the process.\" The album included the boogie-driven \"[[La Grange (song)|La Grange]]\" (written about the [[Chicken Ranch (Texas)|Chicken Ranch]], a notorious brothel in [[La Grange, Texas]], that also inspired the musical ''[[The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas]]''). On the subsequent tour, the band performed sold-out concerts in the US. ZZ Top recorded the live tracks for their 1975 album, ''[[Fandango!]]'', during this tour. ''Fandango!'' was a top-ten album; its single \"[[Tush (ZZ Top song)|Tush]]\" peaked at number 20 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. ''[[Tejas (album)|Tejas]]'', released in 1976, was not as successful or as positively received as their previous efforts, although the album went to number 17 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Tejas \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/tejas-mw0000193395/awards |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> ZZ Top continued the [[Worldwide Texas Tour]] in support of ''Tejas'', though they had been touring for seven years.  The band then went on what was supposed to be a 90-day break from public appearances. Gibbons traveled to Europe, Beard went to [[Jamaica]], and Hill went to [[Mexico]].<ref>di Perna, Alan (July 2, 2008) {{cite web|url= http://www.guitarworld.com/article/zz_top_cars_guitars_three_unlikely_rock_stars?page=0,8 |title= ZZ Top: Cars, Guitars, & Three Unlikely Rock Stars |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081030192921/http://www.guitarworld.com/article/zz_top_cars_guitars_three_unlikely_rock_stars?page=0,8 |archivedate= October 30, 2008}}. ''[[Guitar World]]''.</ref> The break extended to two years, during which Gibbons and Hill grew chest-length [[beard]]s.<ref>Tom Vickers, sleeve notes for ''[[Rancho Texicano]]'' (Warner Bros Records Inc., 2004).</ref>\n\nIn 1979, ZZ Top signed with [[Warner Bros. Records]] and released the album ''[[Deg\u00fcello]]''. While the album went platinum, it only reached number 24 on the ''Billboard'' chart.<ref>{{cite web|title= Deg\u00fcello \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |accessdate= July 28, 2014 |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/deg%C3%BCello-mw0000651021/awards}}</ref> The album produced two popular singles: \"[[I Thank You (song)|I Thank You]]\", a cover of a song recorded by [[Sam & Dave]], and \"[[Cheap Sunglasses]]\". The band remained a popular concert attraction and [[Expect No Quarter Tour|toured in support of ''Deg\u00fcello'']]. In April 1980, ZZ Top made their first appearance in Europe, performing for the German music television show ''[[Rockpalast]]''. Their next album, ''[[El Loco]]'', was released in October 1981, and featured the singles \"[[Tube Snake Boogie]]\", \"[[Pearl Necklace (song)|Pearl Necklace]]\", and \"Leila\".<ref>{{cite web|title= El Loco \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |accessdate= July 28, 2014 |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/el-loco-mw0000197282/awards}}</ref>\n\n===''Eliminator'', ''Afterburner'', and ''Recycler'' (1983\u20131991)===\n[[File:ZZTop.jpg|thumb|230px|right|Hill and Gibbons in 1983]]\nZZ Top's next album was even more successful. ''[[Eliminator (album)|Eliminator]]'', released in March 1983, featured two top-40 singles (\"[[Gimme All Your Lovin']]\" and \"[[Legs (song)|Legs]]\"), and two additional [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Top Rock]] hits (\"[[Got Me Under Pressure]]\" and \"[[Sharp Dressed Man]]\"), with \"Legs\" peaking at number 13 on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Club Play Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title= Eliminator \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/eliminator-mw0000192586/awards |accessdate= July 28, 2013}}</ref> ''Eliminator'' was a critical and commercial success, selling more than 10 million copies,<ref name=\"riaa2\">{{cite web|title= RIAA \u2013 Gold & Platinum Searchable Database \u2013 Eliminator |publisher= [[Recording Industry Association of America]] |url= https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=eliminator#search_section |accessdate= November 19, 2016}}</ref> and several music videos were in regular rotation on MTV. The band also won their first [[MTV Video Music Award]]s in the categories of [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Group Video|Best Group Video]] for \"Legs\", and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]] for \"Sharp Dressed Man\". The music videos were included in their ''[[Greatest Hits (ZZ Top DVD)|Greatest Hits]]'' video, which was later released on DVD and quickly went multiple-platinum.<ref name=\"riaa2\"/> However, the ''Eliminator'' album was not without controversy. According to former stage manager David Blayney in his book \"''Sharp Dressed Men\"'', sound engineer Linden Hudson co-wrote much of the material on the album while serving as a live-in high-tech music teacher to Beard and Gibbons. Despite continued denials by the band, it settled a five-year legal battle with Hudson, paying him $600,000 after he proved he held the copyright to the song \"Thug\".<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Blayney |title= Sharp Dressed Men |location= New York |publisher= [[Hachette Books|Hyperion]] |year= 1994 |isbn= 0-7868-8005-8 |pages= 196\u2013203}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= Deborah |last= Frost |title= ZZ Top - Bad And Worldwide |location= New York |publisher= Rolling Stone Press |year= 1985 |isbn= 0020029500}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Sinclair |title= Tres Hombres: The Story of ZZ Top |publisher= [[Virgin Books|Virgin]] |year= 1986 |isbn= 0-86369-167-6}}</ref>\n\nDespite not selling as many copies as ''Eliminator'', 1985's ''[[Afterburner (ZZ Top album)|Afterburner]]'' became the band's highest-charting album,<ref name=\"Afterburner\">{{cite web|title= Afterburner \u2013 Awards |publisher= AllMusic. All Media Network |accessdate= July 28, 2013 |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/afterburner-mw0000196478/awards}}</ref> racking up sales of five million units.<ref name=\"riaa2\"/> All of the singles from ''Afterburner'' were Top-40 hits, with two (\"Sleeping Bag\" and \"Stages\") hitting number one on the Mainstream Rock chart.<ref name=\"Afterburner\"/> The music video for \"[[Velcro Fly]]\" was choreographed by pop singer [[Paula Abdul]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Paula Abdul \u2013 Times Topics |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= August 5, 2009 |url= http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/a/paula_abdul/index.html |accessdate= December 19, 2010}}</ref> ZZ Top's grueling [[Afterburner World Tour]] lasted well into 1987, which also had the release of ''The ZZ Top Sixpack'', a three-disc collection of ZZ Top's albums from 1970 to 1981, with the exception of ''Deg\u00fcello''. The albums ''ZZ Top's First Album'', ''Rio Grande Mud'', ''Tres Hombres'', ''Fandango'', and ''Tejas'' were remixed to have a more contemporary sound.<ref>{{cite book|first= Bob |last= Merlis |first2= Jim |last2= Bessman |title= ZZ on CD: Meeting The Digital Challenge Head On |location= ZZ Top Six Pack CD Booklet |publisher= Warner Bros Records |year= 1987 |page= 2}}</ref>\n\n''[[Recycler (ZZ Top album)|Recycler]]'', released in 1990, was ZZ Top's last studio album under contract with Warner Records. ''Recycler'' was also the last of a distinct sonic trilogy in the ZZ Top catalogue, marking a return towards a simpler guitar-driven blues sound with less synthesizer and pop bounce than the previous two albums. This move did not entirely suit the fan base that ''Eliminator'' and ''Afterburner'' had built up, and while ''Recycler'' did achieve platinum status, it never matched the sales of those albums. However, the single \"[[My Head's in Mississippi]]\" did reach No. 1 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Album Rock Tracks]] chart that year.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mainstream Rock: Dec 08, 1990 |work= Billboard |accessdate= July 21, 2019 |url= http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/1990-12-08/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks}}</ref>\n\n===Return to guitar-driven sound (1992\u20132003)===\nIn 1992, Warner released ''ZZ Top's Greatest Hits'', along with a new [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]]-style cut, \"Gun Love\", and an [[Elvis Presley|Elvis]]-inflected video, \"[[Viva Las Vegas (song)|Viva Las Vegas]]\". In 1993, ZZ Top inducted a major influence, [[Cream (band)|Cream]], into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].\n\nIn 1994, the band signed a $35 million deal with [[RCA Records]],<ref name=\"rockhonors\">{{cite web|title= VH1 Rock Honors 2007 \u2013 Honorees |year= 2007 |publisher= [[VH1]] |url= http://www.vh1.com/shows/events/rock_honors/_2007/honorees.jhtml |accessdate= December 19, 2010}}</ref> releasing the million-selling ''[[Antenna (ZZ Top album)|Antenna.]]'' Subsequent RCA albums, ''[[Rhythmeen]]'' (1996) and 1999's ''[[XXX (ZZ Top album)|XXX]]'' (the second album to feature live tracks) sold well, but did not reach the levels enjoyed previously. In 2003, ZZ Top released a final RCA album, ''[[Mescalero (album)|Mescalero]]'', an album thick with harsh Gibbons guitar and featuring a [[hidden track]]\u2014a cover version of \"[[As Time Goes By (song)|As Time Goes By.]]\" RCA impresario Clive Davis wanted to do a collaboration record (in the mode of [[Carlos Santana]]'s successful ''Supernatural'') for this album. In an interview in ''[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]]'' magazine, Davis stated that artists [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Dave Matthews]], and [[Wilco]] were among the artists slated for the project. ZZ Top performed \"Tush\" and \"Legs\" as part of the [[Super Bowl XXXI]] halftime show in 1997.\n\nA comprehensive four-CD collection of recordings from the London and Warner Bros. years, ''[[Chrome, Smoke & BBQ]]'', was released in 2003. It featured the band's first single (A- and B-side) and several rare B-side tracks, as well as a radio promotion from 1979, a live track, and several extended dance-mix versions of their biggest MTV hits. Three tracks from Billy Gibbons' pre-ZZ band, the [[Moving Sidewalks]], were also included.\n\n===Critical acclaim and retrospective releases (2004\u20132011)===\nIn 2004, ZZ Top was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]. [[Keith Richards]] of [[the Rolling Stones]] gave the induction speech. ZZ Top gave a brief performance, playing \"La Grange\" and \"Tush\".\n\n[[File:ZZ Top, 26Jun2010.jpg|thumb|left|ZZ Top at the [[Crossroads Guitar Festival]], on June 26, 2010]]\n\nExpanded and remastered versions of the original studio albums from the 1970s and 1980s are currently{{when|date=May 2018}} in production. Marketed as \"Remastered and Expanded\", these releases include additional live tracks which were not present on the original recordings. Three such CDs have been released to date (''Tres Hombres'', ''Fandango!'', and ''Eliminator''). The first two were released in 2006 and use the original mixes free from echo and drum machines, while ''Eliminator'' was released in 2008. The ''Eliminator'' re-release also features a collector's edition version containing a DVD featuring several videos and additional live tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.zztop.com/index.php?module=news_item&news_item_id=116 |title= \"Eliminator\" Reissue Coming March 25th! |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110718161726/http://www.zztop.com/index.php?module=news_item&news_item_id=116 |archivedate= July 18, 2011}}. ZZtop.com. January 14, 2008.</ref>\n\nThe ''Eliminator Collector's Edition'' CD/DVD, celebrating the 25th anniversary of the band's iconic RIAA Diamond Certified album, was released September 10, 2008. The release includes seven bonus tracks and a bonus DVD, including four television performances from ''[[The Tube (TV series)|The Tube]]'' in November 1983.\n\nThe band performed at the 2009 [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] on the final night on March 22, 2009. In July, the band appeared on [[VH1]]'s ''[[VH1 Storytellers|Storytellers]]'', in celebration of their four decades as recording artists.<ref>{{cite press release|title= VH1 To Premiere ZZ Top \"Storytellers\" |url= http://www.icelebz.com/gossips/tv/vh1_to_premiere_zz_top_storytellers_/ |agency= [[All Headline News|AHN]] |date= June 10, 2009 |accessdate= December 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===''La Futura'' and possible sixteenth studio album (2012\u2013present)===\n[[File:ZZ.TOP_2_rkent_at_mac_dot_com.jpg|thumb|ZZ Top at the Alamodome in San Antonio, Texas, November 7, 2013]]\n[[File:ZZ Top 2015.jpg|thumb|ZZ Top performing at the [[Majestic Theatre (San Antonio)|Majestic Theatre]] in San Antonio in 2015]]\nBilly Gibbons stated in an interview in August 2011 that a new album had been recorded, with initial recording taking place in [[Malibu, California]], before moving to Houston, but was still unnamed and had yet to be mixed and mastered.<ref name=\"ucr\"/> Gibbons said that the expected release date was sometime in March or April 2012, but later on a release in the late summer or early fall was announced.<ref name=\"ucr\">{{cite web|title= ZZ Top 'Sowing and Stitching Away' at New Album, Says Billy Gibbons |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-new-album-march-2012/ |accessdate= September 22, 2011 |archivedate= December 25, 2011 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111225070034/http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-new-album-march-2012/}}</ref> The album was subsequently released on  September 11, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://zztop.com/news/90461 |title= La Futura Arrives This September From ZZ Top |website= ZZtop.com |date= August 3, 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121014013711/http://zztop.com/news/90461 |archivedate= October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nEntitled ''[[La Futura]]'', the album was produced by [[Rick Rubin]].<ref>{{cite magazine|first= David |last= Fricke |first2= Eric |last2= Helton |first3= Matthew |last3= Murphy |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/zz-top-billy-gibbons-on-the-bands-next-album-20111129 |title= Billy Gibbons on the band's next album |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |date= November 29, 2011 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= La Futura By ZZ Top |publisher= MP396 |url= http://mp396.com/la-futura-by-zz-top.html  |date= September 13, 2012 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> The first single from the album, \"I Gotsta Get Paid\", debuted in an advertising campaign for [[Jeremiah Weed|Jeremiah Weed Whiskey]] and appears on the soundtrack of the film ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title= Battleship (2012) \u2013 Soundtracks |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1440129/soundtrack |publisher= [[Internet Movie Database]] |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> The song itself is an interpretation of \"25 Lighters\" by Texan hip hop DJ DMD and rappers [[Lil' Keke]] and [[Fat Pat (rapper)|Fat Pat]].<ref>{{cite web|first= Jeff |last= Giles |title= ZZ Top's New Single Based on '90s Rap Song |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-new-single-based-on-90s-rap-song/ |date= May 30, 2012 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> The first four songs from ''La Futura'' debuted on June 5, 2012, on an EP called ''Texicali''.<ref>{{cite web|title= Release Day! |url= http://www.zztop.com/news/81091%20Texicali |website= ZZtop.com |accessdate= July 7, 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140729014435/http://www.zztop.com/news/81091%20Texicali |archivedate= July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[DJ Screw]] was a major influence on the album as well, particularly because Gibbons and Screw both worked with engineer G. L. Moon during the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|first= Ben |last= Ratliff |title= Traveling at the Speed of Molasses |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/09/arts/music/for-zz-top-new-album-la-futura-and-a-tour.html?_r=2& |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= September 6, 2012 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ZZ top Steifel theatre 2016.jpg|ZZ Top in September 2016|thumb]]\nThe band kicked off a North American tour with a concert in Red Bank, New Jersey, at the Count Basie Theatre on March 3, 2015. After rescheduled dates and additions, the tour wrapped up with a concert in Highland Park, Illinois, at the Ravinia Pavilion on August 27, with opening act [[Blackberry Smoke]]. [[Jeff Beck]] joined ZZ Top for seven concerts on the tour.<ref>{{cite web|title= ZZ Top 2015 North American Tour Schedule With Jeff Beck & Blackberry Smoke |website= Zz-top.concerttournewshub |url= http://ZZ-Top.concerttournewshub.com/ |accessdate= March 29, 2015 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151006085950/http://zz-top.concerttournewshub.com/ |archivedate= October 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Upcoming Tour Dates |publisher= Zztop.com |url= http://www.zztop.com/tour/ |accessdate= March 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2016, ZZ Top released a new live album entitled ''Tonite at Midnight: Live Greatest Hits from Around the World''.\n\nIn 2017, ZZ Top announced their \"[[Tonnage Tour|2017 Tonnage Tour]]\" which was to last from February 19 to March 14.<ref>{{cite web|first= Jeff |last= Giles |title= ZZ Top Announce 2017 'Tonnage' Tour |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= October 25, 2016 |accessdate= October 1, 2018 |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-2017-tour/}}</ref> However, they were forced to cancel last few dates of their tour due to the ailment of bassist Dusty Hill.<ref>{{cite web|first= Matthew |last= Wilkening |title= ZZ Top Cancel Remaining 2017 Tour Dates |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= October 17, 2017 |accessdate= October 1, 2018 |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-cancel-2017-tour/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the band announced their six-day Las Vegas run of shows to be held at [[The Venetian Las Vegas|The Venetian]], starting from April 20, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title= ZZ Top returning to Venetian in 2019 |publisher= [[KTNV-TV]] |date= September 24, 2018 |accessdate= October 1, 2018 |url= https://www.ktnv.com/positivelylv/zz-top-returning-to-venetian-in-2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a September 2019 interview with ''[[Ultimate Classic Rock]]'', Hill stated that \"there's a good chance\" ZZ Top will release a follow-up to ''La Futura'': \"We've got a lot in the can. It depends on how we would want to put it together or redo it or whatever. Because it's years of stuff. We just record everything, and then we go, 'Well, no, this didn't quite feel right, right now.'\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Dave |last= Lifton |title= Dusty Hill Says There's a 'Good Chance' of Another ZZ Top Album |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= September 3, 2019 |accessdate= December 22, 2019 |url= https://ultimateclassicrock.com/dusty-hill-new-zz-top-album/}}</ref>\n\n==Other appearances==\nZZ Top performed at the 2008 [[Orange Bowl]] game in [[Miami]], as well as the [[Auto Club 400|Auto Club 500]] [[NASCAR]] event at the [[Auto Club Speedway]] in [[Fontana, California]]. On June 23, 2008, ZZ Top celebrated the release of their first live concert DVD titled ''[[Live from Texas]]'' with the world premiere, a special appearance, and charity auction at the [[Hard Rock Cafe]] in Houston.<ref>{{cite web|title= EVENTS |url= http://www.hardrock.com/Locations/Cafes3/events.aspx?LocationID=56&MIBenumID=3&EventID=31464 |date= June 23, 2008 |website= Hardrock.com |accessdate= October 2, 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110928224155/http://www.hardrock.com/Locations/Cafes3/events.aspx?LocationID=56&MIBenumID=3&EventID=31464 |archivedate= September 28, 2011}}</ref> The DVD was officially released on June 24, 2008. The featured performance was culled from a concert filmed at the Nokia Theater in Grand Prairie, Texas, on November 1, 2007.\n\nOn January 22, 2010, Billy Gibbons accompanied [[Will Ferrell]] and others playing \"[[Free Bird]]\" on [[Conan O'Brien]]'s last ''Tonight Show'' appearance. O'Brien joined in on guitar.<ref>{{cite press release|first= Natalie |last= Rotman |title= O'Brien ends run on 'Tonight' show after 7 months |agency= [[Associated Press]] |date= January 23, 2010 |url= http://newsok.com/obrien-ends-run-on-tonight-show-after-7-months/article/feed/126519 |accessdate= May 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, various media sources reported that the new song \"Flyin' High\" would debut in space. Astronaut and friend of ZZ Top, [[Michael E. Fossum|Michael Fossum]], was given the released single to listen to on his trip to the International Space Station.<ref>{{cite web|title= ZZ Top Debuts New Song In Space |url= http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/zz_top_debuts_new_song_in_space.html |publisher= Ultimate-guitar.com |date= August 6, 2001 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= Spencer |last= Kaufman |title= ZZ Top Premiere New Song 'Flyin' High' on Russian Spacecraft |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= June 9, 2011 |accessdate= September 30, 2019 |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-flyin-high-russian-spacecraft/}}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2014, ZZ Top opened the CMT Awards performing \"La Grange\" with [[Luke Bryan]] and [[Florida Georgia Line]].\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Billy Gibbons]] \u2013 guitar, lead and backing vocals, harmonica (1969\u2013present)\n* [[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]] \u2013 drums, percussion, backing vocals (1969\u2013present)\n* [[Dusty Hill]] \u2013 bass, backing and lead vocals, keyboards (1969\u2013present)\n\n'''Touring substitutes'''\n* John Douglas \u2013 drums, percussion (2002)\n\n'''Session guests'''\n* Pete Tickle \u2013 acoustic guitar on \"Mushmouth Shoutin'\" from ''[[Rio Grande Mud]]'' (1971)\n* [[Terry Manning]] \u2013 synthesizer, drum machine on ''[[Eliminator (album)|Eliminator]]'' (1982)\n* [[James Harman]] \u2013 harmonica on \"[[What's Up with That (ZZ Top song)|What's Up with That]]\" from ''[[Rhythmeen]]'' (1996); ''[[Mescalero (album)|Mescalero]]'' (2002); ''[[La Futura]]'' (2012)\n* Marimbas de Chiapas \u2013 marimba on ''Mescalero'' (2002)\n* [[Dan Dugmore]] \u2013 pedal steel guitar on ''Mescalero'' (2002)\n* Joe Hardy \u2013 piano, Hammond B3 organ on ''La Futura'' (2012)\n* Dave Sardy \u2013 piano, Hammond B3 organ on ''La Futura'' (2012)\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Lanier Greig \u2013 bass, Hammond organ (1969)<ref>{{cite web|first= Jeff |last= Giles |title= Meet the OTHER Three Members of ZZ Top |website= Ultimate Classic Rock |date= February 21, 2014 |accessdate= September 16, 2017 |url= http://ultimateclassicrock.com/zz-top-other-members/}}</ref>\n* Dan Mitchell \u2013 drums (1969)\n* Billy Ethridge \u2013 bass (1969)\n\n'''Touring guests'''\n* [[Jeff Beck]] \u2013 guitar on \"Hey Mr. Millionaire\" from ''[[XXX (ZZ Top album)|XXX]]'' (1999)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|ZZ Top discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n{{div col}}\n* ''[[ZZ Top's First Album]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[Rio Grande Mud]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Tres Hombres]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Fandango!]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Tejas (album)|Tejas]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Deg\u00fcello]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[El Loco]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Eliminator (album)|Eliminator]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Afterburner (ZZ Top album)|Afterburner]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Recycler (album)|Recycler]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Antenna (ZZ Top album)|Antenna]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Rhythmeen]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[XXX (ZZ Top album)|XXX]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Mescalero (album)|Mescalero]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[La Futura]]'' (2012)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Filmography==\nIn addition to recording and performing concerts, ZZ Top has also been involved with films and television. In 1990, the group appeared as the \"band at the party\" in the film ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]''<ref>{{cite web|title= Back to the Future Part III (1990) \u2013 Full Cast & Crew |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0099088/fullcredits#cast |publisher= Internet Movie Database |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> and played the \"Three Men in a Tub\" in the movie ''[[Mother Goose Rock 'n' Rhyme]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mother Goose Rock 'n' Rhyme (1990) \u2013 Full Cast & Crew |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0100192/fullcredits#cast |publisher= Internet Movie Database |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> ZZ Top made further appearances, including the \"Gumby with a Pokey\" episode of ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'' in 2010<ref>{{cite web|title= \"Two and a Half Men\" Gumby with a Pokey (2010) \u2013 Full Cast & Crew |publisher= Internet Movie Database |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1646007/fullcredits#cast |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> and the \"[[Hank Gets Dusted]]\" episode of ''[[King of the Hill]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title= \"King of the Hill\" Hank Gets Dusted (TV episode 2007) |publisher= Internet Movie Database |year= 2007 |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0995437/ |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> The band also [[List of WWE Raw guest stars|guest hosted]] an episode of [[WWE Raw]].<ref>{{cite web|title= WWF Raw Is War \u2013 Episode dated 20 July 2009 |publisher= Internet Movie Database |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0995437/ |year= 2009 |accessdate= July 28, 2014}}</ref> Billy Gibbons also had a recurring role as the father of [[Angela Montenegro]] in the television show ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''; though the character is never named, it is strongly implied that Gibbons is playing himself.<ref>{{cite web|first= Sean |last= Axmaster |title= The Love Story of Bones' Booth and Brennan in 12 Episodes |website= [[Vulture.com]] |date= March 28, 2017 |accessdate= April 22, 2017 |url= http://www.vulture.com/2017/03/bones-booth-brennan-love-story-primer.html}}</ref> Their song \"Sharp Dressed Man\" was one of the theme songs used for the television show ''[[Duck Dynasty]]'', and on the series finale of the show they appeared with [[Si Robertson]] as a vocalist to perform the song on stage during Robertson's retirement party.<ref>{{cite web|title= Legendary Rock Band Makes Surprise Appearance on Final Episode of 'Duck Dynasty' |website= Country Rebel |accessdate= April 22, 2017 |url= https://countryrebel.com/blogs/videos/legendary-rock-group-makes-surprise-appearance-on-final-episode-of-duck-dynasty}}</ref> Black Dahlia Films, led by Jamie Burton Chamberlin, of [[Seattle]] and [[Los Angeles]], has contributed documentaries and [[Live event support|back line screen]] work (the footage on back screens during live shows) and has become an integral part of the band's film-making.<ref>{{cite web|title= Black Dahlia Films + Seattle, WA |url= http://www.blackdahliafilms.com/releases.html |publisher= Blackdahliafilms.com |accessdate= February 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= New ZZ Top tour features West Seattle talent |newspaper= [[West Seattle Herald]] |url= http://www.westseattleherald.com/2012/07/09/features/new-zz-top-tour-features-west-seattle-talent |date= September 7, 2012 |accessdate= February 22, 2015}}</ref> ZZ Top made a guest appearance in the episode \"Sweet Dreams\" (Season 3 Episode 8) of the television show ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'' on November 14, 1984. While the band appears in Luther's dream, once Luther wakes he finds the \"Z\" keychain in the lock of the door to the room he was sleeping in.\n\n==Awards and achievements==\nZZ Top's music videos won multiple [[MTV Video Music Award|VMA]] awards during the 1980s, topping the categories of [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Group Video|Best Group Video]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]], and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]] for \"Legs\", \"Sharp Dressed Man\" and \"[[Rough Boy]]\", respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title= 1986 Video Music Awards |publisher= MTV. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] |url= http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1986/ |accessdate= December 19, 2010}}</ref> Among high honors for ZZ Top have been induction into [[Guitar Center#Hollywood's RockWalk|Hollywood's RockWalk]] in 1994,<ref>{{cite web|title= Hollywood's RockWalk \u2013 ZZ Top |url= http://www.rockwalk.com/inductees/inductee.cfm?id=150 |publisher= [[Guitar Center]] |year= 2007 |accessdate= December 19, 2010}}</ref> the [[Texas House of Representatives]] naming them \"Official Heroes for the State of Texas\",<ref>{{cite news|first= David |last= Yonke |title= ZZ Top: Rocking hard since '69 |newspaper= [[The Blade (Toledo, Ohio)|Toledo Blade]] |date= September 9, 2009 |url= http://www.deltabluesmuseum.org/high/press_090907.asp |accessdate= December 18, 2010}}</ref> a declaration of \"ZZ Top Day\" in Texas by then-governor [[Ann Richards]] on May 4, 1991,<ref>{{cite press release|title= Member News Releases |publisher= [[Texas House of Representatives]] |date= September 29, 2005 |accessdate= December 18, 2010 |url= http://www.house.state.tx.us/news/press-releases/print/?id=1468}}</ref> and induction into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 2004. They were also given commemorative rings by actor [[Billy Bob Thornton]] from the [[VH1 Rock Honors]] in 2007.<ref name=\"rockhonors\"/>\n\nZZ Top has also achieved several chart and album sales feats, including six number-one singles on the [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock chart]]. From the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]], ZZ Top has earned four gold, three platinum and two multiple-platinum album certifications, and one diamond album.<ref name=\"riaa2\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|ZZ Top}}\n*[[ZZ Top equipment]]\n*[[List of artists who reached number one on the U.S. Mainstream Rock chart]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|first=David|last=Thomas|author-link=Dave Thompson (author)|title=Elimination \u2013 The ZZ Top Story|year=1985|location=London|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|isbn=0711907188}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q136591|c=Category:ZZ Top|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no|q=no}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{Curlie|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/Z/ZZ_Top/}}\n*{{Rockhall}}\n\n{{ZZ Top|state=expanded}}\n{{2004 Rock and Roll Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zz Top}}\n[[Category:ZZ Top| ]]\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:American blues rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Hard rock musical groups from Texas]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Houston]]\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Southern rock musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "Howenstein115", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly years (1969\u20131972)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZZ_Top"}
